rofile|6162}}\n\n{{SD Eibar squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leon, Pedro}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00edo Mula]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Murcian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia Imperial players]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia players]]\n[[Category:Levante UD footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:SD Eibar footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish footballer}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Spanish name|S\u00e1nchez|Gil}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Pedro Le\u00f3n\n| image = Pedro Le\u00f3n.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| caption = Le\u00f3n in action for [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| fullname = Pedro Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Gil\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|11|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mula, Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| currentclub = [[SD Eibar|Eibar]]\n| clubnumber = 21\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132002 | youthclubs1 = [[Mule\u00f1o CF|Mule\u00f1o]]\n| youthyears2 = 2002\u20132004 | youthclubs2 = Nueva Vanguardia\n| youthyears3 = 2004 | youthclubs3 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs1 = [[Real Murcia Imperial|Murcia B]] | caps1 = 18 | goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs2 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]] | caps2 = 68 | goals2 = 10\n| years3 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs3 = [[Levante UD|Levante]] | caps3 = 24 | goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs4 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] | caps4 = 33 | goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs5 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps5 = 35 | goals5 = 8\n| years6 = 2010\u20132013 | clubs6 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps6 = 6 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] (loan) | caps7 = 42 | goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 2013\u20132016 | clubs8 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps8 = 93 | goals8 = 11\n| years9 = 2016\u2013 | clubs9 = [[SD Eibar|Eibar]] | caps9 = 73 | goals9 = 12\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132009 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| club-update = 14 December 2019\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Pedro Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Gil''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8pe\u00f0\u027eo le\u02c8on \u02c8sant\u0283e\u03b8}}; born 24 November 1986), known as '''Le\u00f3n''', is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[SD Eibar]] as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]].\n\nAfter making a name for himself at [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] and [[Getafe CF|Getafe]], he transferred to [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in 2010. He left after a sole [[2010\u201311 Real Madrid CF season|season]] troubled by problems with the management, going on to represent Getafe and [[SD Eibar|Eibar]] also in [[La Liga]] and make 291 appearances in the competition (41 goals scored).\n\nA [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spanish under-21]] international, Le\u00f3n represented the nation at the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2009 European Championship]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Murcia===\nBorn in [[Mula, Spain|Mula]], [[Region of Murcia]], Le\u00f3n began his career playing for local [[Mule\u00f1o CF]] and Nueva Vanguardia's youth teams, eventually moving in early 2004 to [[Real Murcia]] to finish his formation.\n\nAfter a spell with the [[Real Murcia Imperial|B-team]], he made his official debut with the main squad on 15 January 2005, in a [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] 1\u20135 loss away loss against [[UE Lleida]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2005/01/16/pagina-20/1361039/pdf.html|title=Golea el Lleida y aleja los fantasmas|trans-title=Lleida rout and chase ghosts away|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=Spanish|date=16 January 2005|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> going on to play a further six matches during [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the season]] and scoring in a 3\u20131 win at neighbouring [[Ciudad de Murcia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2005/05/09/pagina-28/1345637/pdf.html|title=El derbi murciano, para los de Casuco|trans-title=Murcian derby, to Casuco's boys|publisher=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=9 May 2005|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following two seasons, Le\u00f3n became an integral player for Murcia, netting seven goals in the [[2006\u201307 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2006\u201307 campaign]], several from [[Direct free kick|free kicks]], as the side returned to [[La Liga]] after a three-year absence. In January 2007, he was rumoured to be moving to [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] or [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], being speculated that the latter would buy him for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.4 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2011/real-madrids-corner-the-misfortune-of-pedro-leon/|title=Real Madrid\u2019s corner: The misfortune of Pedro Le\u00f3n|publisher=The Hard Tackle|date=11 March 2011|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> Instead, he joined modest [[Levante UD]] in the summer for \u00a32.5 million after rejecting an offer from to renew his contract for [[Euro|\u20ac]]1 million, in a move the club found quite offensive.<ref name=AS>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2007/07/14/mas_futbol/1184394435_850215.html|title=Pedro Le\u00f3n tiene un acuerdo de cinco a\u00f1os con el Levante|trans-title=Pedro Le\u00f3n has a five-year agreement with Levante|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=14 July 2007|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]], Le\u00f3n often underachieved, starting only 11 times from 24 appearances as Levante returned to the second level.<ref>[http://dalje.com/en-sports/real-edge-closer-to-title-after-3-0-win/144027 Real edge closer to title after 3\u20130 win] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509194330/http://dalje.com/en-sports/real-edge-closer-to-title-after-3-0-win/144027|date=9 May 2012}}; Dalje, 27 April 2008</ref> He also ended up training alone, due to problems with management and teammates alike.<ref name=AS/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/1a_division/levante/es/desarrollo/1081967.html|title=Pedro Le\u00f3n: \"Le deseo lo mejor al Murcia desde el domingo\"|trans-title=Pedro Le\u00f3n: \"I wish nothing but the best to Murcia from Sunday onwards\"|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=24 January 2008|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/v/20100929/deportes_murcia/mas-futbol/desencuentros-pedro-leon-20100929.html|title=Los desencuentros de Pedro Le\u00f3n|trans-title=Pedro Le\u00f3n's run-ins|publisher=[[La Verdad (Murcia)|La Verdad]]|language=Spanish|date=29 September 2010|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Valladolid / Getafe===\nOn 13 September 2008, [[Real Valladolid]] bought Le\u00f3n for \u20ac300,000 after a quick negotiation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20090330/quiero-ser-como-pedro-leon_53671184075.html|title=Quiero ser como Pedro Le\u00f3n|trans-title=Bend it like Pedro Le\u00f3n|publisher=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://realvalladolid.elnortedecastilla.es/noticias/2011-01-05/nombres-quiniela-20110105.html|title=Los nombres de la quiniela|trans-title=Names in the lottery|publisher=[[El Norte de Castilla]]|language=Spanish|date=5 January 2011|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> Soon becoming a first-choice, he provided his first [[Assist (football)|assist]] for [[Fabi\u00e1n Canobbio]] on 15 November in a 1\u20130 home win against Real Madrid,<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=252783&cc=5739 Valladolid 1\u20130 Real Madrid]; [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]], 15 November 2008</ref> netting his first for the club a week later in a 3\u20130 away success over [[Villarreal CF]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=253009&cc=5739 Villarreal 0\u20133 Valladolid]; ESPN Soccernet, 22 November 2008</ref>\n\nAfter lengthy negotiations with [[Getafe CF]], with the player appearing very rarely for Valladolid in pre-season, a five-year contract worth around \u20ac4 million was finally arranged in August 2009.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2009/08/25/futbol/equipos/getafe/1251232693.html El Getafe cierra el fichaje de Pedro Le\u00f3n (Getafe complete Pedro Le\u00f3n's signing)]; Marca, 25 August 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Le\u00f3n scored nine goals in official matches during [[2009\u201310 La Liga|the season]] (eight in the league, with nine [[Assist (football)|assists]]), as the [[Madrid|Madrilenians]] finished sixth and [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|qualified]] for the [[UEFA Europa League]] for the second time in their history.<ref name=GUARDIAN>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/oct/21/getafe-pedro-leon|title=Getafe's Pedro Le\u00f3n on the way back to being Pedro Le\u00f3n again|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 October 2013|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Real Madrid===\nOn 15 July 2010, Real Madrid confirmed the transfer of Le\u00f3n for \u20ac10 million.<ref>[http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330009173662/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/Official_Announcement_2010-07-15_21:45:53.htm Official announcement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004094403/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330009173662/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/Official_Announcement_2010-07-15_21%3A45%3A53.htm|date=4 October 2012}}; Real Madrid CF, 15 July 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/pedro-leon-estoy-ilusionado/dasftb/20100715dasdasftb_23/Tes Pedro Le\u00f3n: \"Estoy muy emocionado\" (Pedro Le\u00f3n: \"I am very excited\")]; Diario AS, 15 July 2010 {{in lang|es}}</ref> The player passed the pertinent medical test and was presented the following day.<ref>[http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330009217357/noticia/Noticia/Pedro_Leon_presentation.htm Pedro Le\u00f3n presentation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719211642/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330009217357/noticia/Noticia/Pedro_Leon_presentation.htm|date=19 July 2010}}; Real Madrid CF, 16 July 2010</ref> He made his debut on 4 August in a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] with [[Club Am\u00e9rica]], playing the full match in a 3\u20132 win;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=811864&sec=europe&cc=5739|title=Ronaldo gives Mourinho debut win with Real|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=5 August 2008|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref> in his second appearance, four days later, he scored against the [[LA Galaxy]] as the match ended with the same score.<ref>[http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330011006553/noticia/Cronica/The_Whites_come_back_to_win_in_Rose_Bowl.htm The Whites come back to win in Rose Bowl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815233541/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330011006553/noticia/Cronica/The_Whites_come_back_to_win_in_Rose_Bowl.htm|date=15 August 2010}}; Real Madrid CF, 8 August 2010</ref>\n\nOn 3 November 2010, Le\u00f3n scored his first competitive goal for Real Madrid, combining with [[Karim Benzema]] \u2013 both players had come [[Substitute (association football)|from the bench]] during the second half \u2013 for a [[last-minute goal]] at [[A.C. Milan]] for [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|the group stage]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]], a 2\u20132 draw that sent the Spaniards through to the knockout stage.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000118/match=2002870/index.html Last-ditch Le\u00f3n takes Madrid through in Milan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107014546/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season%3D2011/round%3D2000118/match%3D2002870/index.html|date=7 November 2010}}; UEFA, 3 November 2010</ref> During the course of [[2010\u201311 La Liga|the league season]], however, he appeared rarely: after assuming he would start against [[AJ Auxerre]] in the Champions League in late September, he was immediately dropped from the list of 18 by coach [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]].<ref>[http://www.totalfootballmadness.com/2010/09/30/jose-mourinho-dropped-pedro-leon-for-getting-too-cocky/ Jose Mourinho dropped Pedro Leon for getting too cocky] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706230319/http://www.totalfootballmadness.com/2010/09/30/jose-mourinho-dropped-pedro-leon-for-getting-too-cocky/|date=6 July 2015}}; Total Football Madness, 30 September 2010</ref> Later, he was ridiculed in the press by his own manager when the latter justified his absence.<ref>[http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/39386997 Real Madrid coach Jose Mourinho: Pedro Leon is no Zinedine Zidane] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915015613/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/39386997|date=15 September 2012}}; [[NBC Sports]], 27 September 2010</ref> In early February 2011, both he and teammate [[Fernando Gago]] were dropped from the squad that would face [[Sevilla FC]] in [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|the semi-finals]] of the [[Copa del Rey]], for fighting in training;<ref>[http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2011/02/02/2334327/real-madrid-duo-pedro-leon-and-fernando-gago-involved-in Real Madrid duo Pedro Leon and Fernando Gago involved in training ground altercation]; [[Goal (website)|Goal]], 2 February 2011</ref> Gago was however picked for the next match, whereas Le\u00f3n was not.\n\nChelsea renewed their interest in taking Le\u00f3n on loan in the winter [[transfer window]],<ref>[http://www.insidefutbol.com/2011/01/29/chelsea-send-proposal-to-real-madrid-for-pedro-leon/36533/ Chelsea send proposal to Real Madrid for Pedro Leon]; Inside Futbol, 29 January 2011</ref> but no move took place \u2013 he reportedly blamed Mourinho for blocking the move.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/real-madrid-midfielder-pedro-leon-3314805|title=Pedro Leon: Mourinho blocked my move to Chelsea|publisher=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> In March 2011, after the market had closed, [[H\u00e9rcules CF]] tried to acquire the player on loan following [[Tote (footballer)|Tote]]'s severe knee injury, but Real Madrid refused again.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/03/09/futbol/equipos/hercules/1299658923.html|title=El Real Madrid dice \"no\" al H\u00e9rcules por Pedro Le\u00f3n|trans-title=Real Madrid say \"no\" to H\u00e9rcules for Pedro Le\u00f3n|publisher=Marca|language=Spanish|date=9 March 2011|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Getafe return===\nAt the end of the 2011 summer transfer window, Le\u00f3n returned to former club Getafe on a [[2011\u201312 La Liga|season]]-long loan.<ref>[http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330065342508/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/Official_Announcement_2011-08-31.htm Official announcement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915030656/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330065342508/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/Official_Announcement_2011-08-31.htm|date=15 September 2011}}; Real Madrid CF, 31 August 2011</ref> He scored the first goal of his second spell on 1 October, with a spectacular long-range strike at [[M\u00e1laga CF]] in a 2\u20133 loss;<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/323969?cc=5739 Malaga hit back to sink Getafe]; ESPN Soccernet, 1 October 2011</ref> the move was extended for [[2012\u201313 La Liga|the following campaign]].<ref>[http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2012/06/28/3205301/getafe-ficha-a-pedro-le%C3%B3n-por-un-a%C3%B1o-m%C3%A1s-a-coste-cero Getafe 'ficha' a Pedro Le\u00f3n por un a\u00f1o m\u00e1s a coste cero (Getafe 'sign' Pedro Le\u00f3n for another year for nothing)]; Goal, 28 June 2012 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Le\u00f3n signed for Getafe on a permanent basis. On 6 October 2013, he scored twice in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Real Betis]], netting his first through a 40-meter free kick.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/373142/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|title=Getafe keep on climbing|publisher=ESPN FC|date=6 October 2013|accessdate=27 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127064512/http://espnfc.com/en/report/373142/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|archivedate=27 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLe\u00f3n was not allowed to be registered for the start of [[2014\u201315 La Liga|2014\u201315]], as the club had exceeded the \u20ac17 million salary cap.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/deportes/futbol/liga-primera/201409/03/prohibe-inscribir-pedro-leon-20140903120725-rc.html|title=Pedro Le\u00f3n, sin ficha por el l\u00edmite salarial|trans-title=Pedro Le\u00f3n, unregistered due to salary cap|publisher=La Verdad|language=Spanish|date=3 September 2014|accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> The situation was finally resolved on 24 November, the day of the player's 28th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2014/11/24/futbol/equipos/getafe/1416854527.html|title=El mejor regalo de cumplea\u00f1os|trans-title=The best birthday present|publisher=Marca|language=Spanish|date=24 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Eibar===\nOn 5 July 2016, after Getafe's [[2015\u201316 La Liga|relegation]], Le\u00f3n signed a two-year deal with [[SD Eibar]] also in the top tier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdeibar.com/noticia/sd-eibar-ficha-a-pedro-leon-sanchez-gil-por-dos-temporadas|title=SD Eibar ficha a Pedro Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Gil por dos temporadas|trans-title=SD Eibar sign Pedro Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Gil for two seasons|publisher=SD Eibar|language=es|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> He scored a career-best ten goals in [[2016\u201317 La Liga|his first season]] \u2013 only behind [[Sergi Enrich]]'s 11 in the squad<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bizkaia.eldesmarque.com/athletic-club/noticias/59680-enrich-pedro-leon-y-kike-garcia-el-50-de-los-goles-del-eibar|title=Enrich, Pedro Le\u00f3n y Kike Garc\u00eda, el 50% de los goles del Eibar|trans-title=Enrich, Pedro Le\u00f3n and Kike Garc\u00eda, 50% of Eibar's goals|publisher=El Desmarque|language=Spanish|date=19 April 2017|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\u2013 but missed the vast majority of [[2017\u201318 La Liga|the following]] after replapsing from a left knee injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/eibar/2017/11/15/5a0c5dd9e5fdea65108b4644.html|title=Pedro Le\u00f3n recae de su lesi\u00f3n y volver\u00e1 a pasar por el quir\u00f3fano|trans-title=Pedro Le\u00f3n relapses from injury and will visit operating room again|publisher=Marca|language=Spanish|date=15 November 2017|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nLe\u00f3n made his debut for the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain national under-21 team]] on 31 January 2007. On 6 February, [[I\u00f1aki S\u00e1ez]] played him again in a friendly with [[England national under-21 football team|England]], in which he was replaced by [[Juan Mata]] in a 2\u20132 away draw.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6322149.stm England U21 2\u20132 Spain U21]; [[BBC Sport]], 6 February 2007</ref> He also featured in the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|2009 European Championship qualifier]] against [[Georgia national under-21 football team|Georgia]], coming on for [[Alejandro Alfaro]] in the second half a 1\u20130 away win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/barca/bojan-ejercio-como-revulsivo-en-su-debut-5551514|title=Bojan ejerci\u00f3 como revulsivo en su debut|trans-title=Bojan was the spark in his debut|publisher=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=Spanish|date=6 June 2007|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nPicked in the 23-man squad for [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|the final stages]] in Sweden, Le\u00f3n scored in the final game against [[Finland national under-21 football team|Finland]], but the nation did not progress from the group stage.<ref>[http://www.goal.com/en/news/2378/euro-u-21-2009/2009/06/22/1341149/european-u-21-championship-spain-beat-finland-but-fail-to Spain beat Finland but fail to qualify]; Goal, 22 June 2009</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLe\u00f3n's older brother, [[Luis Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez]], is a [[Road bicycle racing|road bicycle racer]]. His other brother Antonio also played football, but the [[Indoor soccer|indoor]] variety.<ref name=\"PAIS\">[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/futbol/sobrevalorado/ciclismo/machacado/elpepudep/20090105elpepidep_25/Tes \"El f\u00fatbol est\u00e1 sobrevalorado, y el ciclismo, machacado\" (\"Football is overrated, and cycling, through the dirt\")]; [[El Pa\u00eds]], 5 January 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref name=GUARDIAN/>\n\nLe\u00f3n was not his surname, but he carried it as a [[middle name]] in memory of his grandfather and eldest brother, who both died in 2006 (the latter in a motorbike accident), and tended to just go by the name Le\u00f3n rather than Le\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez (as his two brothers), also celebrating his goals by pointing to the sky.<ref name=\"PAIS\"/>\n\n==Club statistics==\n<!-- PLEASE CHANGE THE DATE OF THE UPDATE BELOW! Thank You!-->\n{{updated|23 February 2019}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/pedro-leon-sanchez-gil/20001/|title=Pedro Le\u00f3n|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"3\"|Cup\n!col