{"title_page": "John Naylor (astrologer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''John Naylor''' was a British astrologer.\n\nHe was the son of [[R. H. Naylor]], and on his death in 1952, took over his column in the ''[[Sunday Express]]''.<ref name=Express>{{cite news|last1=Membery|first1=York|title=Horoscopes: Tales of the expected|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/196242/Horoscopes-Tales-of-the-expected|accessdate=6 October 2014|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=29 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nNaylor later became the resident astrologer at the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' until his retirement in 1986.<ref name=\"Campion2012\">{{cite book|author=Dr Nicholas Campion|title=Astrology and Popular Religion in the Modern West: Prophecy, Cosmology and the New Age Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLpd_38zNzkC&pg=PT299|date=1 September 2012|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.]]|isbn=978-1-4094-6149-4|pages=298\u2013299}}</ref> He was succeeded at the Daily Mail by [[Nicholas Campion]].<ref name=AA>{{cite web|title=Interview with Nick Campion - Part 2 |url=http://www.astrologicalassociation.com/pages/articles/journalArticles/nickPart2.php |website=Astrological Association |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014070809/http://www.astrologicalassociation.com/pages/articles/journalArticles/nickPart2.php |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naylor, John}}\n[[Category:British astrologers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century astrologers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''John Naylor''' was a British astrologer.\n\nHe was the son of [[R. H. Naylor]], and on his death in 1952, took over his column in the ''[[Sunday Express]]''.<ref name=Express>{{cite news|last1=Membery|first1=York|title=Horoscopes: Tales of the expected|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/196242/Horoscopes-Tales-of-the-expected|accessdate=6 October 2014|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=29 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nNaylor later became the resident astrologer at the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' until his retirement in 1986.<ref name=\"Campion2012\">{{cite book|author=Dr Nicholas Campion|title=Astrology and Popular Religion in the Modern West: Prophecy, Cosmology and the New Age Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLpd_38zNzkC&pg=PT299|date=1 September 2012|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.]]|isbn=978-1-4094-6149-4|pages=298\u2013299}}</ref> He was succeeded at the Daily Mail by [[Nicholas Campion]].<ref name=AA>{{cite web|title=Interview with Nick Campion - Part 2 |url=http://www.astrologicalassociation.com/pages/articles/journalArticles/nickPart2.php |website=Astrological Association |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014070809/http://www.astrologicalassociation.com/pages/articles/journalArticles/nickPart2.php |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naylor, John}}\n[[Category:British astrologers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century astrologers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Naylor_(astrologer)"}
{"title_page": "Kris Versteeg", "text_new": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Kris Versteeg\n| image = Kris Versteeg - Chicago Blackhawks.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Versteeg with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|5|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Lethbridge, Alberta|Lethbridge]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 176\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Right wing]] / [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left wing]]\n| shoots = Right\n| played_for = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]<br>[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]<br>[[Philadelphia Flyers]]<br>[[Florida Panthers]]<br>[[Carolina Hurricanes]]<br>[[Los Angeles Kings]]<br>[[Calgary Flames]]<br>[[Avangard Omsk]]<br>[[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]]<br>[[HK Nitra|Nitra]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = 134th overall\n| draft_year = 2004\n| draft_team = [[Boston Bruins]]\n| career_start = 2006\n| career_end = 2020\n}}\n\n'''Kristopher Royce Versteeg''' (born May 13, 1986) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]]. During his career, he played for the [[Chicago Blackhawks]], [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], [[Philadelphia Flyers]], [[Florida Panthers]], [[Carolina Hurricanes]], [[Los Angeles Kings]], [[Calgary Flames]], [[Avangard Omsk]], [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] and [[HK Nitra|Nitra]]. Versteeg is a two-time [[Stanley Cup]] champion with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in [[2010 Stanley Cup Finals|2010]] and [[2015 Stanley Cup Finals|2015]].\n\nOriginally selected 134th overall in the [[2004 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Boston Bruins]], he played with the club's minor league affiliate, the [[Providence Bruins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), for parts of two seasons before being traded to the Blackhawks. Versteeg continued playing in the AHL with the Blackhawks' affiliates until making his NHL debut during the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]]. The following campaign, he received a nomination for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as the NHL's best rookie. In his second full season with the Blackhawks, he helped the club win the [[Stanley Cup]] in [[2010 Stanley Cup playoffs|2010]]. Following Chicago's Cup win, Versteeg played for the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], [[Philadelphia Flyers]] and [[Florida Panthers]] before being traded back to Chicago during the [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314 season]], winning the [[Stanley Cup]] again in [[2015 Stanley Cup Finals|2015]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career and Boston Bruins===\nVersteeg was drafted 134th overall in the [[2004 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Boston Bruins]], after a four-year [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) career spanning from [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]] to [[2005\u201306 WHL season|2005\u201306]] and spent with the [[Lethbridge Hurricanes]], [[Kamloops Blazers]] and [[Red Deer Rebels]]. During his time with Lethbridge, he played with future Blackhawks teammate [[Brent Seabrook]] for three seasons. Versteeg made his professional debut, playing in the final 13 games of the [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]] season with Boston's [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Providence Bruins]].\n\n===Chicago Blackhawks===\nVersteeg remained with Providence for the beginning of [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]] before being traded by Boston on February 3, 2007, along with a conditional draft pick, to the Chicago Blackhawks for [[Brandon Bochenski]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/sport/nhl/article_1255309.php/Blackhawks_ship_Bochenski_to_the_Bruins|title=Blackhawks ship Bochenski to the Bruins|publisher=m&c.com|date=2007-02-03|accessdate=2008-11-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404084111/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/sport/nhl/article_1255309.php/Blackhawks_ship_Bochenski_to_the_Bruins|archivedate=2012-04-04}}</ref> As a result, he moved within the AHL to Chicago's minor league affiliate, the [[Norfolk Admirals (AHL)|Norfolk Admirals]]. Versteeg then played for the [[Rockford IceHogs]] in [[2007\u201308 AHL season|2007\u201308]], as Chicago switched its AHL affiliation. He made his NHL debut that season as he was called up for a total of 13 games, recording two goals and two assists.\n\n[[File:Kris Versteeg.jpg|thumb|left|Versteeg during the 2009\u201310 season, in his first tenure with the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Blackhawks]].|200px]]\nVersteeg played his first full season with the Blackhawks in [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]. On January 1, 2009, he scored the opening goal of the [[2009 Winter Classic]] held at [[Wrigley Field]] against the [[Detroit Red Wings]]. Finishing the season with 22 goals and 53 points, second in rookie scoring to [[Bobby Ryan]] of the [[Anaheim Ducks]], he was nominated for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as rookie of the year along with Ryan and goaltender [[Steve Mason (ice hockey)|Steve Mason]] of the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] for his efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ryan, Versteeg, Mason selected as Calder Trophy nominees|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=276043|accessdate=2009-04-23|date=2009-04-22|publisher=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]}}</ref> Mason ended up winning the Calder.\n\nVersteeg's entry-level contract expired after the 2008\u201309 season, which would typically have made him a [[restricted free agent]] (RFA).  However, a clerical error in which the Blackhawks failed to tender qualifying offers to their pending RFAs by the league deadline led to speculation Versteeg and several of his teammates would become [[unrestricted free agents]]. As a result, the [[NHL Players' Association]] (NHLPA) filed a grievance on the players' behalf. Shortly thereafter, on July 8, 2009, he re-signed with the Blackhawks to a three-year contract, worth nearly [[USD|US]]$9 million.<ref>{{cite news | first=Len | last=Ziehm |authorlink= | title=Blackhawks, Kris Versteeg have deal | date=2009-07-08 | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | url =http://www.suntimes.com/sports/hockey/blackhawks/1656279,CST-SPT-hawk08.article | pages = | accessdate = 2009-07-08 | language = }}</ref>\n\nVersteeg's offensive production dropped in his second full NHL season, recording 20 goals and 44 points over 79 games. In the 2010 playoffs, he added 14 points in 22 games, helping the Blackhawks to a [[Stanley Cup]] championship, defeating the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in the Finals. His name was originally misspelled \"Kris Vertseeg\" when engraved on the Stanley Cup, but was quickly corrected.<ref>{{cite news | title='Vertseeg' has name misspelled on Cup | date=2010-09-29 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/09/29/vertseeg-misspelled-cup/ | accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Toronto Maple Leafs===\nDue to [[salary cap]] restraints, the Blackhawks were forced to trade away several players in the off-season, including Versteeg. On June 30, 2010, he was dealt to the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] along with the rights to prospect [[Bill Sweatt]] in exchange for forwards [[Viktor St\u00e5lberg]], [[Chris DiDomenico]] and [[Philippe Paradis]].  He recorded his first [[Gordie Howe hat trick]] (a goal, an assist and a fight) with the Maple Leafs in a game against the [[Ottawa Senators]] on October 9, 2010; he scored against [[Pascal Leclaire]], assisted on a goal by [[Phil Kessel]] and fought [[Mike Fisher (ice hockey)|Mike Fisher]].\n\n===Philadelphia Flyers===\nAfter recording 35 points over 53 games with the Maple Leafs in [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311]], he was traded for the second time in his career on February 14, 2011. Toronto sent him to the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in exchange for first-round and third-round draft picks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs send Versteeg to Flyers.|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=353885|accessdate=2011-02-14|date=2011-02-14|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> Versteeg joined the team that he helped defeat in the previous season's Stanley Cup Finals and scored seven goals to go with four assists during the remainder of the regular season. He scored one goal during the [[2011 Stanley Cup Playoffs]], which came in the final game of Philadelphia's fourth game 5\u20131 loss to the [[Boston Bruins]] in the second round.\n\n===Florida Panthers===\nOn July 1, 2011, the Flyers traded Versteeg to the [[Florida Panthers]] for a second-round pick (either 2012 or 2013\u2014 Florida's choice) and a third-round pick in the [[2012 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Philadelphia Flyers|date=2011-07-01|title=Flyers Trade Versteeg To Panthers|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=568197|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> The trade came just a few hours after the Flyers announced the signing of [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr]].\n[[File:Kris Versteeg 2016.jpg|right|thumb|Versteeg during his brief tenure with the [[Los Angeles Kings|Kings]].|200px]]\n\n===Return to Chicago===\nOn November 14, 2013, the Panthers traded Versteeg, along with Philippe Lefebvre, to the Chicago Blackhawks for [[Jimmy Hayes (ice hockey)|Jimmy Hayes]] and [[Dylan Olsen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/eye-on-hockey/24234141/kris-versteeg-traded-back-to-blackhawks-by-panthers|title=Kris Versteeg traded back to Blackhawks by Panthers| publisher =[[CBS Sports]] | date = 2013-11-14 | accessdate = 2013-11-16|first=Brian|last= Stubits}}</ref> Since Versteeg's jersey #32, which he wore during his first stint with the club was being worn by [[Michal Rozs\u00edval]], Versteeg opted to wear #23 upon his return to the club. On June 15, 2015, Versteeg won his second Stanley Cup with the Chicago Blackhawks in a 2-0 Game 6 victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning in the Stanley Cup Final.\n\n===Carolina Hurricanes===\nOn Sept 11, 2015, Versteeg was again traded by the Blackhawks due to salary cap constraints, along with [[Joakim Nordstr\u00f6m|Joakim Nordstrom]], to the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] along with a 3rd round pick in the [[2017 NHL Entry Draft]] for a 5th round pick in the [[2017 NHL Entry Draft]] and two prospects. The move was done to make more cap space available for [[Marcus Kr\u00fcger|Marcus Kruger]], who was re-signed the next day. In the following [[2015-16 NHL season|2015\u201316]] season, Versteeg transitioned to the Hurricanes quickly and was used on the club's top scoring lines throughout the year.\n\n===Los Angeles Kings===\nVersteeg produced 33 points in 63 games before on February 28, 2016, he was familiarly traded at the trade deadline to the [[Los Angeles Kings]] in exchange for [[Valentin Zykov]] and a conditional 5th round pick in [[2016 NHL Entry Draft|2016]] (if Los Angeles advanced to the 2016 Western Conference Final, failed).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/14867007/los-angeles-kings-acquire-kris-versteeg-carolina-hurricanes-valentin-zykov-draft-pick | title =  Hurricanes forward Kris Versteeg joining Kings, traded for a 7th time | publisher = [[ESPN]] | date = 2016-02-28 | accessdate = 2016-02-28}}</ref> Acquired by the Kings for depth in their playoff run, the team would fail to make it deep, losing in the first round to the [[San Jose Sharks]]. In his stint with the Kings, Versteeg scored 5 points in 14 games, while adding 2 more in the team's 5 playoff appearances.\n\n===Calgary Flames===\nOn July 25, 2016, as a free agent from the Kings, Versteeg opted to pause his NHL career in agreeing to sign a one-year deal with the [[SC Bern]] of the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] NLA.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.scb.ch/no_cache/news/top-meldung/newsitem/kris-versteeg-zum-scb.html | title = Kris Versteeg signs with SCB | publisher = [[SC Bern]] | date = 2016-07-25 | accessdate = 2016-07-25 | language = German | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160725161934/http://www.scb.ch/no_cache/news/top-meldung/newsitem/kris-versteeg-zum-scb.html | archive-date = 2016-07-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> However, he later failed to pass the medical exam in early September and therefore the contract was voided.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rts.ch/sport/hockey/lna/7995547-hockey-lna-kris-versteeg-quitte-deja-berne.html|title= Kris Versteeg quits Bern| language=fr-CH| date = 2016-09-06 | access-date=2016-09-06 | publisher = rts.ch}}</ref> On September 9, 2016, Versteeg returned to continue his career in the NHL in agreeing to join the [[Edmonton Oilers]] at their training camp on a [[Hockey contracts#Professional Try Out|professional tryout]] basis.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://twitter.com/DarrenDreger/status/774329431523463170?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw | title = Versteeg officially signs PTO with Oilers | publisher = [[Twitter]] | author = Darren Dreger | date = 2016-09-09 | accessdate = 2016-09-09}}</ref>\n\nAfter a successful training camp with the Oilers, on October 11, 2016, Versteeg rejected a contract offer from the Oilers, opting to instead join provincial rivals the Calgary Flames on a one-year deal worth $900,000 in the NHL.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/flames-sign-versteeg-to-one-year-contract/c-282559856 | title = Flames sign Versteeg to one-year deal | publisher = [[Calgary Flames]] | date = 2016-10-11 | accessdate = 2016-10-11}}</ref> Versteeg enjoyed a productive first season in Calgary, establishing himself as a key contributor on the powerplay. His eight goals with the man-advantage led the team, while his 15 total goals finished tied for fifth. Versteeg finished second in team scoring during the Flames' round-one series against the [[Anaheim Ducks]], tallying a goal and three assists as the Flames were swept in four games.\n\nWith Versteeg and Flames management both interested in coming to terms on a new contract, they agreed to a one-year, $1.75 million contract on June 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flames, Versteeg complete one-year deal |url=https://www.tsn.ca/flames-versteeg-completing-one-year-deal-1.792490 |website=TSN |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> Versteeg played 24 games for the club after suffering a hip injury on November 24, and having surgery on December 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Kristen |title=Versteeg on the mend after hip surgery |url=https://calgarysun.com/sports/hockey/nhl/calgary-flames/versteeg-on-the-mend-after-hip-surgery |website=Calgary Sun |accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nOn September 1, 2018, Versteeg signed his first overseas contract, joining Russian club, [[Avangard Omsk]] of the [[Kontinental Hockey League]] (KHL).<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0414\u0432\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041a\u0443\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u044d\u043d\u043b\u0438 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0433 - \u0432 \"\u0410\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\" |url=http://www.hawk.ru/news/32091/ |website=www.hawk.ru |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |language=ru-RU |date=September 1, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 KHL season|2018\u201319]] season, Versteeg was limited to just 11 games with Omsk, recording 5 points, before opting to leave for the remainder of the season with Swedish club, [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] of the SHL on February 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web| publisher = [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] | url = https://www.vaxjolakers.se/artikel/moxdajrt2-4af7d/kanadensisk-forward-klar-for-klubben | title = Canadian forward Versteeg signs with Vaxjo | date = 2019-02-07 | accessdate = 2019-02-07 | language = Swedish}}</ref> Versteeg contributed down the tail end of the regular season with 11 points through 12 games. He continued his scoring pace in the post season for the Lakers with 6 points in 7 games.\n\nAt the conclusion of the Lakers' season, Versteeg left the organization to return to North America. On April 22, 2019, Versteeg signed a one-year contract with the [[Rockford IceHogs]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and would be named team captain.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.icehogs.com/news/?article_id=6697 | title = Rockford agrees to terms with two-time Stanley Cup champ Kris Versteeg | publisher = [[Rockford IceHogs]] | date = 2019-04-22 | accessdate = 2019-04-22}}</ref> He last played for the IceHogs during the [[2007\u201308 AHL season|2007\u201308 season]] and the team was still affiliated with the Blackhawks. After appearing in just six games through injury, he announced he was leaving the team on November 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.secondcityhockey.com/2019/11/17/20969156/chicago-blackhawks-rockford-icehogs-kris-versteeg-mutually-terminate-ahl-contract-2019 |title=Kris Versteeg, Rockford IceHogs mutually terminate AHL contract |website=SB Nation |date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb| url = https://theahl.com/icehogs-versteeg-part-ways | title = IceHogs, Versteeg part ways | publisher = [[American Hockey League]] | date = November 17, 2019 | accessdate = November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith the intention to play out the remainder of the season before retiring, Versteeg signed a contract to join his brother Mitch at HK Nitra of the Tipsport liga on November 20, 2019.<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://www.hockeynitra.com/?q=clanok/potvrdzujeme-kris-versteeg-bude-hrat-za-nitru/1347 | title = Confirmed! Kris Versteeg to Nitra | publisher = [[HK Nitra]] | language = Slovak | date = November 20, 2019 | accessdate = November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVersteeg's younger brother [[Mitch Versteeg|Mitch]] is currently a [[defenceman]] with the [[HK Nitra]] of the [[Tipsport liga (hockey) |Tipsport liga]] in [[Slovakia]].\n\nVersteeg has developed a reputation within the NHL for his habit of singing in public, as evidenced by his recitation of a portion of [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]]'s \"[[Glamorous (Fergie song)|Glamorous]]\" on Mouthpiece Sports, as well as performing an altered version of [[LMFAO]]'s \"Yes\" during the Chicago Blackhawks' Stanley Cup victory parade. Versteeg also sang [[Kanye West]]'s verse of the [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]] song \"[[American Boy (Estelle song)|American Boy]]\" in a video clip on Blackhawks TV during his time with Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lzAVPwFsnrE|title=Kris Versteeg Raps Fergie in the Chicago Blackhawks Locker Room | publisher =[[YouTube]] | date = 2008-11-04 | accessdate = 2010-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LGSU0OX4qYA|title=Kris Versteeg Raps At The Chicago Blackhawks Rally | publisher =[[YouTube]] | date = 2010-06-10 | accessdate = 2010-08-15}}</ref> He continued this tradition during the 2015 Championship Rally by singing [[Macklemore]]'s \"And We Danced\" along with [[Joakim Nordstr\u00f6m]].\n\nVersteeg has a tattoo on his upper right arm that reads \"[[2010 Stanley Cup Finals|06 \u2022 09 \u2022 10]]\" in commemoration of the date he won the Stanley Cup as a member of the Blackhawks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/leafs-beat/versteeg-has-mark-of-a-champion/article1717697/|title=Versteeg has mark of a champion | newspaper =The Globe and Mail | date = 2010-09-21 | accessdate = 2011-07-11}}</ref>\n\nVersteeg and his wife, Brittany have two sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://blackhawks.nhl.com/club/blogpost.htm?id=40053 | title = Versteeg family welcomes new addition | publisher = [[Chicago Blackhawks]] | date = 2015-06-03 | accessdate = 2015-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.tabertimes.com/sports/2016/08/17/versteeg-embarking-on-new-journey/ | title = Versteeg embarking on new journey | publisher = [[Taber Times]] | date = 2016-08-17 | accessdate = 2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season|Regular&nbsp;season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| [[Lethbridge Hurricanes]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 57\n| 8\n| 10\n| 18\n| 32\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| Lethbridge Hurricanes\n| WHL\n| 68\n| 16\n| 33\n| 49\n| 85\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2004\u201305 WHL season|2004\u201305]]\n| Lethbridge Hurricanes\n| WHL\n| 68\n| 22\n| 30\n| 52\n| 68\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 4\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2005\u201306 WHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Kamloops Blazers]]\n| WHL\n| 14\n| 6\n| 6\n| 12\n| 24\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| 2005\u201306\n| [[Red Deer Rebels]]\n| WHL\n| 57\n| 10\n| 26\n| 36\n| 103\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Providence Bruins]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 13\n| 2\n| 4\n| 6\n| 13\n| 3\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 6\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| Providence Bruins\n| AHL\n| 43\n| 22\n| 27\n| 49\n| 19\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2006\u201307\n| [[Norfolk Admirals (AHL)|Norfolk Admirals]]\n| AHL\n| 27\n| 4\n| 19\n| 23\n| 20\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 2\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[2007\u201308 AHL season|2007\u201308]]\n| [[Rockford IceHogs]]\n| AHL\n| 56\n| 18\n| 31\n| 49\n| 174\n| 12\n| 6\n| 5\n| 11\n| 6\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308]]\n| [[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 13\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 78\n| 22\n| 31\n| 53\n| 55\n| 17\n| 4\n| 8\n| 12\n| 22\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310]]\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 79\n| 20\n| 24\n| 44\n| 35\n| 22\n| 6\n| 8\n| 14\n| 14\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n| NHL\n| 53\n| 14\n| 21\n| 35\n| 29\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| 2010\u201311\n| [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n| NHL\n| 27\n| 7\n| 4\n| 11\n| 24\n| 11\n| 1\n| 5\n| 6\n| 12\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[2011\u201312 NHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| [[Florida Panthers]]\n| NHL\n| 71\n| 23\n| 31\n| 54\n| 49\n| 7\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 8\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2012\u201313 NHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Florida Panthers\n| NHL\n| 10\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| Florida Panthers\n| NHL\n| 18\n| 2\n| 5\n| 7\n| 9\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2013\u201314\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 63\n| 10\n| 19\n| 29\n| 27\n| 15\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 4\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 61\n| 14\n| 20\n| 34\n| 35\n| 12\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| 6\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2015\u201316 NHL season|2015\u201316]]\n| [[Carolina Hurricanes]]\n| NHL\n| 63\n| 11\n| 22\n| 33\n| 36\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| 2015\u201316\n| [[Los Angeles Kings]]\n| NHL\n| 14\n| 4\n| 1\n| 5\n| 6\n| 5\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2016\u201317 NHL season|2016\u201317]]\n| [[Calgary Flames]]\n| NHL\n| 69\n| 15\n| 22\n| 37\n| 46\n| 4\n| 1\n| 3\n| 4\n| 4\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| Calgary Flames\n| NHL\n| 24\n| 3\n| 5\n| 8\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2018\u201319 KHL season|2018\u201319]]\n| [[Avangard Omsk]]\n| [[Kontinental Hockey League|KHL]]\n| 11\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2018\u201319 SHL season|2018\u201319]]\n| [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]]\n| [[Swedish Hockey League|SHL]]\n| 12\n| 4\n| 7\n| 11\n| 4\n| 7\n| 4\n| 2\n| 6\n| 4\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2019\u201320 KHL season|2019\u201320]]\n| Dinamo Riga\n| KHL\n| 52\n| 57\n| 42\n| 99\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2019\u201320 Slovak Extraliga season|2019\u201320]]\n| [[HK Nitra|Nitra]]\n| [[Tipsport liga (hockey)|SVK]]\n| 3\n| 0\n| 3\n| 3\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | NHL totals\n! 643\n! 149\n! 209\n! 358\n! 374\n! 93\n! 18\n! 30\n! 48\n! 70\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40em\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Year\n! Team\n! Event\n! Result\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2004 IIHF World U18 Championships|2004]]\n| [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|Canada]]\n| [[IIHF World U18 Championship|WJ18]]\n| 4th\n| 7\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=4 | Junior totals\n! 7\n! 0\n! 2\n! 2\n! 4\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award\n! Year\n!\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|[[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n|-\n| [[NHL All-Rookie Team]]\n| [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2009]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Stanley Cup]] (Chicago Blackhawks)\n| [[2010 Stanley Cup Finals|2010]], [[2015 Stanley Cup Finals|2015]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Spengler Cup]] (Canada)\n| [[2019 Spengler Cup|2019]]\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kris Versteeg}}\n* {{Ice hockey stats |nhl=8471346 |elite= |espn= |euro= |hr=v/verstkr01 |hockeydb=69003 |legends=21392 |tsn=kris-versteeg }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Versteeg, Kris}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Avangard Omsk players]]\n[[Category:Boston Bruins draft picks]]\n[[Category:Calgary Flames players]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey right wingers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Carolina Hurricanes players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Blackhawks players]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lethbridge]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Kamloops Blazers players]]\n[[Category:Lethbridge Hurricanes players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Kings players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Admirals players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Flyers players]]\n[[Category:Providence Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Red Deer Rebels players]]\n[[Category:Rockford IceHogs (AHL) players]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs players]]\n[[Category:V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers players]]\n[[Category:HK Nitra players]]\n[[Category:Slovak Extraliga players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in Russia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Kris Versteeg\n| image = Kris Versteeg - Chicago Blackhawks.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Versteeg with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|5|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Lethbridge, Alberta|Lethbridge]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 176\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Right wing]] / [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left wing]]\n| shoots = Right\n| played_for = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]<br>[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]<br>[[Philadelphia Flyers]]<br>[[Florida Panthers]]<br>[[Carolina Hurricanes]]<br>[[Los Angeles Kings]]<br>[[Calgary Flames]]<br>[[Avangard Omsk]]<br>[[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]]<br>[[HK Nitra|Nitra]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = 134th overall\n| draft_year = 2004\n| draft_team = [[Boston Bruins]]\n| career_start = 2006\n| career_end = 2020\n}}\n\n'''Kristopher Royce Versteeg''' (born May 13, 1986) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]]. During his career, he played for the [[Chicago Blackhawks]], [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], [[Philadelphia Flyers]], [[Florida Panthers]], [[Carolina Hurricanes]], [[Los Angeles Kings]], [[Calgary Flames]], [[Avangard Omsk]], [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] and [[HK Nitra|Nitra]]. Versteeg is a two-time [[Stanley Cup]] champion with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in [[2010 Stanley Cup Finals|2010]] and [[2015 Stanley Cup Finals|2015]].\n\nOriginally selected 134th overall in the [[2004 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Boston Bruins]], he played with the club's minor league affiliate, the [[Providence Bruins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), for parts of two seasons before being traded to the Blackhawks. Versteeg continued playing in the AHL with the Blackhawks' affiliates until making his NHL debut during the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]]. The following campaign, he received a nomination for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as the NHL's best rookie. In his second full season with the Blackhawks, he helped the club win the [[Stanley Cup]] in [[2010 Stanley Cup playoffs|2010]]. Following Chicago's Cup win, Versteeg played for the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], [[Philadelphia Flyers]] and [[Florida Panthers]] before being traded back to Chicago during the [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314 season]], winning the [[Stanley Cup]] again in [[2015 Stanley Cup Finals|2015]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career and Boston Bruins===\nVersteeg was drafted 134th overall in the [[2004 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Boston Bruins]], after a four-year [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) career spanning from [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]] to [[2005\u201306 WHL season|2005\u201306]] and spent with the [[Lethbridge Hurricanes]], [[Kamloops Blazers]] and [[Red Deer Rebels]]. During his time with Lethbridge, he played with future Blackhawks teammate [[Brent Seabrook]] for three seasons. Versteeg made his professional debut, playing in the final 13 games of the [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]] season with Boston's [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Providence Bruins]].\n\n===Chicago Blackhawks===\nVersteeg remained with Providence for the beginning of [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]] before being traded by Boston on February 3, 2007, along with a conditional draft pick, to the Chicago Blackhawks for [[Brandon Bochenski]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/sport/nhl/article_1255309.php/Blackhawks_ship_Bochenski_to_the_Bruins|title=Blackhawks ship Bochenski to the Bruins|publisher=m&c.com|date=2007-02-03|accessdate=2008-11-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404084111/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/sport/nhl/article_1255309.php/Blackhawks_ship_Bochenski_to_the_Bruins|archivedate=2012-04-04}}</ref> As a result, he moved within the AHL to Chicago's minor league affiliate, the [[Norfolk Admirals (AHL)|Norfolk Admirals]]. Versteeg then played for the [[Rockford IceHogs]] in [[2007\u201308 AHL season|2007\u201308]], as Chicago switched its AHL affiliation. He made his NHL debut that season as he was called up for a total of 13 games, recording two goals and two assists.\n\n[[File:Kris Versteeg.jpg|thumb|left|Versteeg during the 2009\u201310 season, in his first tenure with the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Blackhawks]].|200px]]\nVersteeg played his first full season with the Blackhawks in [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]. On January 1, 2009, he scored the opening goal of the [[2009 Winter Classic]] held at [[Wrigley Field]] against the [[Detroit Red Wings]]. Finishing the season with 22 goals and 53 points, second in rookie scoring to [[Bobby Ryan]] of the [[Anaheim Ducks]], he was nominated for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as rookie of the year along with Ryan and goaltender [[Steve Mason (ice hockey)|Steve Mason]] of the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] for his efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ryan, Versteeg, Mason selected as Calder Trophy nominees|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=276043|accessdate=2009-04-23|date=2009-04-22|publisher=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]}}</ref> Mason ended up winning the Calder.\n\nVersteeg's entry-level contract expired after the 2008\u201309 season, which would typically have made him a [[restricted free agent]] (RFA).  However, a clerical error in which the Blackhawks failed to tender qualifying offers to their pending RFAs by the league deadline led to speculation Versteeg and several of his teammates would become [[unrestricted free agents]]. As a result, the [[NHL Players' Association]] (NHLPA) filed a grievance on the players' behalf. Shortly thereafter, on July 8, 2009, he re-signed with the Blackhawks to a three-year contract, worth nearly [[USD|US]]$9 million.<ref>{{cite news | first=Len | last=Ziehm |authorlink= | title=Blackhawks, Kris Versteeg have deal | date=2009-07-08 | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | url =http://www.suntimes.com/sports/hockey/blackhawks/1656279,CST-SPT-hawk08.article | pages = | accessdate = 2009-07-08 | language = }}</ref>\n\nVersteeg's offensive production dropped in his second full NHL season, recording 20 goals and 44 points over 79 games. In the 2010 playoffs, he added 14 points in 22 games, helping the Blackhawks to a [[Stanley Cup]] championship, defeating the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in the Finals. His name was originally misspelled \"Kris Vertseeg\" when engraved on the Stanley Cup, but was quickly corrected.<ref>{{cite news | title='Vertseeg' has name misspelled on Cup | date=2010-09-29 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/09/29/vertseeg-misspelled-cup/ | accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Toronto Maple Leafs===\nDue to [[salary cap]] restraints, the Blackhawks were forced to trade away several players in the off-season, including Versteeg. On June 30, 2010, he was dealt to the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] along with the rights to prospect [[Bill Sweatt]] in exchange for forwards [[Viktor St\u00e5lberg]], [[Chris DiDomenico]] and [[Philippe Paradis]].  He recorded his first [[Gordie Howe hat trick]] (a goal, an assist and a fight) with the Maple Leafs in a game against the [[Ottawa Senators]] on October 9, 2010; he scored against [[Pascal Leclaire]], assisted on a goal by [[Phil Kessel]] and fought [[Mike Fisher (ice hockey)|Mike Fisher]].\n\n===Philadelphia Flyers===\nAfter recording 35 points over 53 games with the Maple Leafs in [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311]], he was traded for the second time in his career on February 14, 2011. Toronto sent him to the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in exchange for first-round and third-round draft picks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs send Versteeg to Flyers.|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=353885|accessdate=2011-02-14|date=2011-02-14|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> Versteeg joined the team that he helped defeat in the previous season's Stanley Cup Finals and scored seven goals to go with four assists during the remainder of the regular season. He scored one goal during the [[2011 Stanley Cup Playoffs]], which came in the final game of Philadelphia's fourth game 5\u20131 loss to the [[Boston Bruins]] in the second round.\n\n===Florida Panthers===\nOn July 1, 2011, the Flyers traded Versteeg to the [[Florida Panthers]] for a second-round pick (either 2012 or 2013\u2014 Florida's choice) and a third-round pick in the [[2012 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Philadelphia Flyers|date=2011-07-01|title=Flyers Trade Versteeg To Panthers|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=568197|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> The trade came just a few hours after the Flyers announced the signing of [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr]].\n[[File:Kris Versteeg 2016.jpg|right|thumb|Versteeg during his brief tenure with the [[Los Angeles Kings|Kings]].|200px]]\n\n===Return to Chicago===\nOn November 14, 2013, the Panthers traded Versteeg, along with Philippe Lefebvre, to the Chicago Blackhawks for [[Jimmy Hayes (ice hockey)|Jimmy Hayes]] and [[Dylan Olsen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/eye-on-hockey/24234141/kris-versteeg-traded-back-to-blackhawks-by-panthers|title=Kris Versteeg traded back to Blackhawks by Panthers| publisher =[[CBS Sports]] | date = 2013-11-14 | accessdate = 2013-11-16|first=Brian|last= Stubits}}</ref> Since Versteeg's jersey #32, which he wore during his first stint with the club was being worn by [[Michal Rozs\u00edval]], Versteeg opted to wear #23 upon his return to the club. On June 15, 2015, Versteeg won his second Stanley Cup with the Chicago Blackhawks in a 2-0 Game 6 victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning in the Stanley Cup Final.\n\n===Carolina Hurricanes===\nOn Sept 11, 2015, Versteeg was again traded by the Blackhawks due to salary cap constraints, along with [[Joakim Nordstr\u00f6m|Joakim Nordstrom]], to the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] along with a 3rd round pick in the [[2017 NHL Entry Draft]] for a 5th round pick in the [[2017 NHL Entry Draft]] and two prospects. The move was done to make more cap space available for [[Marcus Kr\u00fcger|Marcus Kruger]], who was re-signed the next day. In the following [[2015-16 NHL season|2015\u201316]] season, Versteeg transitioned to the Hurricanes quickly and was used on the club's top scoring lines throughout the year.\n\n===Los Angeles Kings===\nVersteeg produced 33 points in 63 games before on February 28, 2016, he was familiarly traded at the trade deadline to the [[Los Angeles Kings]] in exchange for [[Valentin Zykov]] and a conditional 5th round pick in [[2016 NHL Entry Draft|2016]] (if Los Angeles advanced to the 2016 Western Conference Final, failed).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/14867007/los-angeles-kings-acquire-kris-versteeg-carolina-hurricanes-valentin-zykov-draft-pick | title =  Hurricanes forward Kris Versteeg joining Kings, traded for a 7th time | publisher = [[ESPN]] | date = 2016-02-28 | accessdate = 2016-02-28}}</ref> Acquired by the Kings for depth in their playoff run, the team would fail to make it deep, losing in the first round to the [[San Jose Sharks]]. In his stint with the Kings, Versteeg scored 5 points in 14 games, while adding 2 more in the team's 5 playoff appearances.\n\n===Calgary Flames===\nOn July 25, 2016, as a free agent from the Kings, Versteeg opted to pause his NHL career in agreeing to sign a one-year deal with the [[SC Bern]] of the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] NLA.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.scb.ch/no_cache/news/top-meldung/newsitem/kris-versteeg-zum-scb.html | title = Kris Versteeg signs with SCB | publisher = [[SC Bern]] | date = 2016-07-25 | accessdate = 2016-07-25 | language = German | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160725161934/http://www.scb.ch/no_cache/news/top-meldung/newsitem/kris-versteeg-zum-scb.html | archive-date = 2016-07-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> However, he later failed to pass the medical exam in early September and therefore the contract was voided.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rts.ch/sport/hockey/lna/7995547-hockey-lna-kris-versteeg-quitte-deja-berne.html|title= Kris Versteeg quits Bern| language=fr-CH| date = 2016-09-06 | access-date=2016-09-06 | publisher = rts.ch}}</ref> On September 9, 2016, Versteeg returned to continue his career in the NHL in agreeing to join the [[Edmonton Oilers]] at their training camp on a [[Hockey contracts#Professional Try Out|professional tryout]] basis.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://twitter.com/DarrenDreger/status/774329431523463170?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw | title = Versteeg officially signs PTO with Oilers | publisher = [[Twitter]] | author = Darren Dreger | date = 2016-09-09 | accessdate = 2016-09-09}}</ref>\n\nAfter a successful training camp with the Oilers, on October 11, 2016, Versteeg rejected a contract offer from the Oilers, opting to instead join provincial rivals the Calgary Flames on a one-year deal worth $900,000 in the NHL.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/flames-sign-versteeg-to-one-year-contract/c-282559856 | title = Flames sign Versteeg to one-year deal | publisher = [[Calgary Flames]] | date = 2016-10-11 | accessdate = 2016-10-11}}</ref> Versteeg enjoyed a productive first season in Calgary, establishing himself as a key contributor on the powerplay. His eight goals with the man-advantage led the team, while his 15 total goals finished tied for fifth. Versteeg finished second in team scoring during the Flames' round-one series against the [[Anaheim Ducks]], tallying a goal and three assists as the Flames were swept in four games.\n\nWith Versteeg and Flames management both interested in coming to terms on a new contract, they agreed to a one-year, $1.75 million contract on June 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flames, Versteeg complete one-year deal |url=https://www.tsn.ca/flames-versteeg-completing-one-year-deal-1.792490 |website=TSN |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> Versteeg played 24 games for the club after suffering a hip injury on November 24, and having surgery on December 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Kristen |title=Versteeg on the mend after hip surgery |url=https://calgarysun.com/sports/hockey/nhl/calgary-flames/versteeg-on-the-mend-after-hip-surgery |website=Calgary Sun |accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nOn September 1, 2018, Versteeg signed his first overseas contract, joining Russian club, [[Avangard Omsk]] of the [[Kontinental Hockey League]] (KHL).<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0414\u0432\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041a\u0443\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u044d\u043d\u043b\u0438 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0433 - \u0432 \"\u0410\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\" |url=http://www.hawk.ru/news/32091/ |website=www.hawk.ru |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |language=ru-RU |date=September 1, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 KHL season|2018\u201319]] season, Versteeg was limited to just 11 games with Omsk, recording 5 points, before opting to leave for the remainder of the season with Swedish club, [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] of the SHL on February 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web| publisher = [[V\u00e4xj\u00f6 Lakers]] | url = https://www.vaxjolakers.se/artikel/moxdajrt2-4af7d/kanadensisk-forward-klar-for-klubben | title = Canadian forward Versteeg signs with Vaxjo | date = 2019-02-07 | accessdate = 2019-02-07 | language = Swedish}}</ref> Versteeg contributed down the tail end of the regular season with 11 points through 12 games. He continued his scoring pace in the post season for the Lakers with 6 points in 7 games.\n\nAt the conclusion of the Lakers' season, Versteeg left the organization to return to North America. On April 22, 2019, Versteeg signed a one-year contract with the [[Rockford IceHogs]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and would be named team captain.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.icehogs.com/news/?article_id=6697 | title = Rockford agrees to terms with two-time Stanley Cup champ Kris Versteeg | publisher = [[Rockford IceHogs]] | date = 2019-04-22 | accessdate = 2019-04-22}}</ref> He last played for the IceHogs during the [[2007\u201308 AHL season|2007\u201308 season]] and the team was still affiliated with the Blackhawks. After appearing in just six games through injury, he announced he was leaving the team on November 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.secondcityhockey.com/2019/11/17/20969156/chicago-blackhawks-rockford-icehogs-kris-versteeg-mutually-terminate-ahl-contract-2019 |title=Kris Versteeg, Rockford IceHogs mutually terminate AHL contract |website=SB Nation |date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb| url = https://theahl.com/icehogs-versteeg-part-ways | title = IceHogs, Versteeg part ways | publisher = [[American Hockey League]] | date = November 17, 2019 | accessdate = November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith the intention to play out the remainder of the season before retiring, Versteeg signed a contract to join his brother Mitch at HK Nitra of the Tipsport liga on November 20, 2019.<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://www.hockeynitra.com/?q=clanok/potvrdzujeme-kris-versteeg-bude-hrat-za-nitru/1347 | title = Confirmed! Kris Versteeg to Nitra | publisher = [[HK Nitra]] | language = Slovak | date = November 20, 2019 | accessdate = November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVersteeg's younger brother [[Mitch Versteeg|Mitch]] is currently a [[defenceman]] with the [[HK Nitra]] of the [[Tipsport liga (hockey) |Tipsport liga]] in [[Slovakia]].\n\nVersteeg has developed a reputation within the NHL for his habit of singing in public, as evidenced by his recitation of a portion of [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]]'s \"[[Glamorous (Fergie song)|Glamorous]]\" on Mouthpiece Sports, as well as performing an altered version of [[LMFAO]]'s \"Yes\" during the Chicago Blackhawks' Stanley Cup victory parade. Versteeg also sang [[Kanye West]]'s verse of the [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]] song \"[[American Boy (Estelle song)|American Boy]]\" in a video clip on Blackhawks TV during his time with Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lzAVPwFsnrE|title=Kris Versteeg Raps Fergie in the Chicago Blackhawks Locker Room | publisher =[[YouTube]] | date = 2008-11-04 | accessdate = 2010-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LGSU0OX4qYA|title=Kris Versteeg Raps At The Chicago Blackhawks Rally | publisher =[[YouTube]] | date = 2010-06-10 | accessdate = 2010-08-15}}</ref> He continued this tradition during the 2015 Championship Rally by singing [[Macklemore]]'s \"And We Danced\" along with [[Joakim Nordstr\u00f6m]].\n\nVersteeg has a tattoo on his upper right arm that reads \"[[2010 Stanley Cup Finals|06 \u2022 09 \u2022 10]]\" in commemoration of the date he won the Stanley Cup as a member of the Blackhawks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/leafs-beat/versteeg-has-mark-of-a-champion/article1717697/|title=Versteeg has mark of a champion | newspaper =The Globe and Mail | date = 2010-09-21 | accessdate = 2011-07-11}}</ref>\n\nVersteeg and his wife, Brittany have two sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://blackhawks.nhl.com/club/blogpost.htm?id=40053 | title = Versteeg family welcomes new addition | publisher = [[Chicago Blackhawks]] | date = 2015-06-03 | accessdate = 2015-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.tabertimes.com/sports/2016/08/17/versteeg-embarking-on-new-journey/ | title = Versteeg embarking on new journey | publisher = [[Taber Times]] | date = 2016-08-17 | accessdate = 2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season|Regular&nbsp;season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| [[Lethbridge