{"title_page": "John Munro (poet)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''John Munro''' {{postnominals|MC}} (1889\u20131918), was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] soldier and poet who won the [[Military Cross]] during the [[World War I|First World War]]. He fell in action with the 7th Battalion [[Seaforth Highlanders]]. Munro was born in Swordale, [[Isle of Lewis]] and, writing in his native [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]] as '''Iain Rothach''', came to be ranked by critics alongside the major war poets. A collection of his poetry was prepared and given to a local minister for safekeeping and publication, but the manuscript was scandalously lost. Derick Thomson - the venerable poet and Professor of Celtic Studies at [[Glasgow]] - hailed Munro's work in his ''Companion to Gaelic Scotland'' as being: \"the first strong voice of the new Gaelic verse of the 20th century\".\n\n==Further reading==\n* Trevor Royle.  ''In Flanders Field'' (anthology of Scottish war poetry).\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scottishradiance.com/poet/poet0101.htm Poem by Munro], in Gaelic and English.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, John}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish World War I poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:People from the Isle of Lewis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish Gaelic poets]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Seaforth Highlanders officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''John Munro''' {{postnominals|MC}} (1889\u20131918), was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] soldier and poet who won the [[Military Cross]] during the [[World War I|First World War]]. He fell in action with the 7th Battalion [[Seaforth Highlanders]]. Munro was born in Swordale, [[Isle of Lewis]] and, writing in his native [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]] as '''Iain Rothach''', came to be ranked by critics alongside the major war poets. A collection of his poetry was prepared and given to a local minister for safekeeping and publication, but the manuscript was scandalously lost. Derick Thomson - the venerable poet and Professor of Celtic Studies at [[Glasgow]] - hailed Munro's work in his ''Companion to Gaelic Scotland'' as being: \"the first strong voice of the new Gaelic verse of the 20th century\".\n\n==Further reading==\n* Trevor Royle.  ''In Flanders Field'' (anthology of Scottish war poetry).\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scottishradiance.com/poet/poet0101.htm Poem by Munro], in Gaelic and English.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, John}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish World War I poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:People from the Isle of Lewis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish Gaelic poets]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Seaforth Highlanders officers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Munro_(poet)"}
{"title_page": "Robert Siciliano", "text_new": "{{autobiography|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Robert Siciliano\n| image              = Robert_L._Siciliano.jpg\n| caption            = Self-portrait photograph\n| occupation = Author, Security Analyst\n| notable_works = \u201cIdentity Theft Privacy\u201d (2018)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siciliano |first1=Robert |title=Identity Theft Privacy |date=2018-07-23 |publisher=Tross Publishing |pages=129 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41451429-identity-theft-privacy |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>, \u201cThe Safety Minute\u201d (2003)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siciliano |first1=Robert |title=The safety minute : living on high alert : how to take control of your personal security and prevent fraud |date=2003-05-28 |publisher=Safety Zone Press |isbn=9780964812673 |pages=153 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5764592-the-safety-minute |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|05|25}}\n| website            = {{URL|safr.me}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Siciliano''' (born May 25, 1968) is an American security analyst, [[author]] and media personality. He delivers presentations throughout the [[United States]] and [[Canada]] on [[identity theft]] protection and personal [[security]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts say laptops are the weak link in data security |url=https://www.helpnetsecurity.com/2006/09/13/experts-say-laptops-are-the-weak-link-in-data-security/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Help Net Security |date=13 September 2006}}</ref>, including [[self-defense]].<ref name=\"Mint\">{{cite news |title=Expert Interview with Robert Siciliano on Identity Theft |url=https://www.mint.com/personal-finance-interviews/expert-interview-with-robert-siciliano-on-identity-theft |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Mint |date=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nSiciliano has appeared on United States-based television programming such as ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'', ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]'', [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], [[Fox News]], [[CNBC]], ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[Tyra Banks Show]]'', ''Sally Jesse Show'', ''[[Montel Williams]]'', ''[[Maury Povich Show]]'', ''Gayle King Show'' and the ''[[Howard Stern Show]]''.<ref name=\"99series\">{{cite book |title=99 things you wish you knew before-- your identity was stolen : your guide to protecting yourself from identity theft and computer fraud |date=2011-10-01 |publisher=The 99 Series 2011 |isbn=0983212295 |page=201 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13123022-99-things-you-wish-you-knew-before-your-identity-was-stolen}}</ref> In addition, he has been quoted in American news print publications such as ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Boston Globe]]'', and ''Entrepreneur''.<ref name=\"99series\"/>\nSiciliano serves on the board of directors for the Identity Theft Resource Center,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lacey |first1=Charity |title=Robert Siciliano of IDTheftSecurity.com Joins ITRC Board of Directors |url=https://www.idtheftcenter.org/robert-siciliano-of-idtheftsecurity-com-joins-itrc-board-of-directors/ |website=Identity Theft Resource Center |accessdate=26 May 2019 |date=2 October 2014}}</ref> contributes to the Realtor Safety Initiative Team for Realtor Safety Week,<ref>{{cite web |title=Safety Resources for Associations and Brokerages |url=https://www.nar.realtor/safety/safety-resources-for-associations-and-brokerages |website=www.nar.realtor |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and is a regular keynote speaker at security-related events.\n\n== Life and career ==\nRobert Siciliano grew up in and around [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. Robert earned his certification in Private Investigations from Boston University, as well as his certificate as a Certified Speaking Professional from the NSA (National Speakers Association).<ref>{{cite web |title=The Switch to the Chip Card \u2013 One Year Later |url=https://newsroom.mastercard.com/people/robertsiciliano/ |website=MasterCard Social Newsroom |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> For the last 20+ years, Siciliano has been refining his rhetoric, content, message to carry out his  mission of informing the public on the issues and solutions surrounding security issues.<ref name=\"99series\"/> \n\nTalk show host [[Montel Williams]] was the first to broadcast Siciliano nationally.<ref name=\"99series\"/>  Show producers worked with Siciliano to develop scenarios where he would socially engineer his way into resident's homes in Elizabethtown, New Jersey, posing as a utility worker.<ref>{{cite news |title=Home safe home |url=https://www.sheknows.com/home-and-gardening/articles/7887/is-your-home-a-security-risk/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=SheKnows |date=17 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks]], Siciliano provided commentary as a news correspondent in regards to many security issues such as school shootings<ref>{{cite news |title=Homeland Security gives pointers on surviving shooting sprees {{!}} {{!}} dailyitem.com |url=https://www.dailyitem.com/homeland-security-gives-pointers-on-surviving-shooting-sprees/article_d75c3fed-db91-5556-b6a4-d2faf5cf1bb8.amp.html |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=www.dailyitem.com}}</ref>, terrorist hoaxes<ref>{{cite news |title=Anderson Cooper 'Swatted' as Celebrity 911 Hoax Hits East Coast |url=https://www.newsmax.com/thewire/anderson-cooper-swatted-celebrity-911-hoax/2013/05/08/id/503413/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Newsmax |date=8 May 2013}}</ref>, [[workplace violence]], privacy issues<ref>{{cite web |title=How the FBI Cracked the iPhone Case \u2026 With a Little Help From Outside |url=https://computer.howstuffworks.com/how-fbi-cracked-the-iphone-case.htm |website=HowStuffWorks |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en |date=7 April 2016}}</ref>, child abductions, and travel security.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Trends in Travel Security |url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/slideshows/new-trends-in-travel-security |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Travel + Leisure |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, lawyers representing the legendary rock band [[Led Zeppelin]] asked Robert Siciliano to surrender the domain www.ledzeppelin.com which he had owned for 5 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lieberman |first1=Allyson |title=WHAT\u2019S IN A NAME? A LAWSUIT \u2013 CELEBRITIES ARE MOVING IN ON WEBSITES BEARING THEIR NAMES |url=https://nypost.com/1999/10/15/whats-in-a-name-a-lawsuit-celebrities-are-moving-in-on-websites-bearing-their-names/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=New York Post |date=15 October 1999 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, Siciliano conducted an experiment that tested the ease of buying and deploying a retail ATM and as a result raised a few eyebrows in the ATM industry. He was able to purchase an ATM for $750.00 US on Craigslist.org, then program and deploy the retail ATM without any red tape or paperwork registration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leyden |first1=John |title=Second-hand ATM trade opens up fraud risk |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/11/18/second_hand_atm_fraud_risk/ |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=www.theregister.co.uk |date=2009-11-18 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2013, Siciliano ran the 117th edition of the mass-participation Boston Marathon as a charity runner for Boston Children's Hospital. Roberts experience during the bombing was chronicled by the Boston Globe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Teitell |first1=Beth |title=Some agonize over fleeing Marathon bombing scene |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/style/2013/05/08/boston-marathon-heroes-are-lauded-some-who-didn-rush-help-grapple-with-guilt/SNUKlSFLDMKTmz3Sen69dP/story.html |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=2013-05-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Keynotes ===\n\n* The Western States Director Education Foundation Symposium<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsdef.org/pastagendas.cfm|title=Western States Director Education Foundation|date=2005-11-01|publisher=WSDEF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011103150/http://www.wsdef.org/pastagendas.cfm|archivedate=2008-10-11|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* National Association of Credit Managers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacmchicago.org/omaha/home_omaha.htm|title=NACM Midwest|date=2007-04-19|publisher=Nacmchicago.org|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Massachusetts Association of Realtors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marealtor.net/conv/schedule.htm|title=Conference Schedule|date=|publisher=Marealtor.net|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Industrial Asset Management Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamc.org/pressSept2004.shtml|title=Industrial Asset Management Council|publisher=IAMC|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613063040/http://iamc.org/pressSept2004.shtml|archivedate=2010-06-13|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Meetings Professionals International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpiweb.org/CMS/mpiweb/mpicontent.aspx?id=16434|title=Meeting Professionals International|publisher=Mpiweb.org|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120903200118/http://www.mpiweb.org/CMS/mpiweb/mpicontent.aspx?id=16434|archive-date=2012-09-03|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Louisiana State University<ref>[http://www.lsu.edu/safety/pdfs/Safety_Programs.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060902213629/http://www.lsu.edu/safety/pdfs/Safety_Programs.pdf|date=September 2, 2006}}</ref>\n*United Bankers Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/crime-law-enforcement-corrections/criminal-offenses-fraud/11706822-1.html|title=Bankers' bank event focuses on tech security, ID theft &#124; North America > United States from|date=|publisher=AllBusiness.com|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Tools of the Trade REALTOR Expo<ref>{{cite news |title=Get Your Game On at Realcomp\u2019s Tools Expo by Attending Robert Siciliano\u2019s Presentation\u2026 |url=https://realcomp.moveinmichigan.com/News-Events/Feature-2018/April-2018/Robert_Siciliano_Get_Your_Game_On |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=realcomp.moveinmichigan.com}}</ref>\n* Parady Financial<ref>{{cite web |title=Protect Your Wealth Summit October |url=https://www.paradyfinancial.com/protectyourwealthoctober/ |website=Parady Financial |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n* National Association of Realtors<ref>{{cite news |title=Realtors Highlight the Importance of Defending Against a Data Breach |url=http://athensceo.com/news/2018/11/realtors-highlight-importance-defending-against-data-breach/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Athens CEO |language=en}}</ref>\n* Michigan Credit Union League<ref>{{cite news |title=Identity Theft Big Topic at Fall Leadership Development Conference |url=https://www.mcul.org/News?article_id=28113 |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Michigan Credit Union League}}</ref>\n* Global Business Travel Association<ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago BTA Q1 2015 Chapter Meeting |url=https://chicagobta.org/meetinginfo.php?id=23&ts=1423500415 |website=Chicago Business Travel Association |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Realtors Triple Play<ref>{{cite news |title=Agent & Client ID Theft Security & Awareness \u2013 Triple Play REALTOR\u00ae Convention & Trade Expo |url=https://www.realtorstripleplay.com/tripleplay-sessions/2018/agent-client-id-theft-security-awareness/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Realtors Triple Play}}</ref>\n\n==Books authored==\nSiciliano is the author of 5 books:\n\n# Siciliano, Robert. The Safety Minute: How To Be Safe In The Streets At Home And Abroad So You Can Save Your Life! 1996. SafetyZone Press. Boston, MA. {{ISBN|0-9648126-2-2}}\n# Siciliano, Robert. The Safety Minute: Living On High Alert; How To Take Control Of Your Personal Security And Prevent Fraud. 2003. SafetyZone Press. Boston, MA. {{ISBN|0-9648126-7-3}}\n# Siciliano, Robert. 99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Identity Was Stolen. 2011. McAfee. Florida, NY. {{ASIN|B0060GBP8Y}}<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year= |title=99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Identity Was Stolen |publisher=Amazon |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.amazon.com/Things-Before-Identity-Stolen-ebook/dp/B0060GBP8Y |accessdate=September 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n# Siciliano, Robert. 99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Mobile Device Was Hacked. 2012. McAfee. Florida, NY. {{ISBN|1937801195}}<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year= |title=99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Mobile Device Was Hacked |publisher=Amazon |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.amazon.com/Things-Before-Mobile-Device-Hacked/dp/1937801195/ref=sr_1_5?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1347128068&sr=1-5 |accessdate=September 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n#Siciliano, Robert. Identity Theft Privacy. 2018. Tross Consulting. Tempe, AZ. {{ISBN|978-0-9969500-8-4}}. \n\nHe has also contributed to the development of five other books, including ones such as '' Protect your business against threats internally and externally''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Friedmann |first1=Susan |title=Riches in Niches: How to Make It Big in a Small Market: Easy Read Comfort Edition |date=2009 |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |isbn=9781442956933 |page=143 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqHiz7C7_i4C&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=%22robert+siciliano%22+Riches+In+Niches&source=bl&ots=gSgMzdJ85R&sig=ACfU3U0Gv0_CzOsUDznv0I75IcQg7qIzbg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3xYmj06_iAhVBTd8KHVyRBjkQ6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22robert%20siciliano%22%20Riches%20In%20Niches&f=false |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and ''Riches In Niches, How to make it big in a small market''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Friedmann |first1=Susan |title=Riches in Niches: How to Make It Big in a Small Market: Easy Read Comfort Edition |date=2009 |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |isbn=9781442956933 |page=143 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqHiz7C7_i4C&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=%22robert+siciliano%22+%22Riches+In+Niches%22&source=bl&ots=gShEzbH56Q&sig=ACfU3U1zwdKjDObMuErdyyqBNI0M7myEsA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQrI7omuniAhUEIqwKHWc9DXgQ6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22robert%20siciliano%22%20%22Riches%20In%20Niches%22&f=false |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://safr.me/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2892079}}\n\n===Appearances in media===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www1.whdh.com/features/articles/uncovers/BO130883/ |title=Counterfeit cash machines |publisher=whdh.com |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2010-03-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928201758/http://www1.whdh.com/features/articles/uncovers/BO130883/ |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,464794,00.html |title=Internet Scams Targeting Growing Out of Work Population |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-siciliano/social-media-messages-tel_b_484698.html |title=Social Media Messages Telling Too Much? |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=2010-03-03 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siciliano, Robert}}\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American male actors]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{autobiography|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Robert Siciliano\n| image              = Robert_L._Siciliano.jpg\n| caption            = Self-portrait photograph\n| occupation = Author, Security Analyst\n| notable_works = \u201cIdentity Theft Privacy\u201d (2018)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siciliano |first1=Robert |title=Identity Theft Privacy |date=2018-07-23 |publisher=Tross Publishing |pages=129 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41451429-identity-theft-privacy |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>, \u201cThe Safety Minute\u201d (2003)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siciliano |first1=Robert |title=The safety minute : living on high alert : how to take control of your personal security and prevent fraud |date=2003-05-28 |publisher=Safety Zone Press |isbn=9780964812673 |pages=153 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5764592-the-safety-minute |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|05|25}}\n| website            = {{URL|safr.me}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Siciliano''' (born May 25, 1968) is an American security analyst, [[author]] and media personality. He delivers presentations throughout the [[United States]] and [[Canada]] on [[identity theft]] protection and personal [[security]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts say laptops are the weak link in data security |url=https://www.helpnetsecurity.com/2006/09/13/experts-say-laptops-are-the-weak-link-in-data-security/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Help Net Security |date=13 September 2006}}</ref>, including [[self-defense]].<ref name=\"Mint\">{{cite news |title=Expert Interview with Robert Siciliano on Identity Theft |url=https://www.mint.com/personal-finance-interviews/expert-interview-with-robert-siciliano-on-identity-theft |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Mint |date=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nSiciliano has appeared on United States-based television programming such as \"[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]],\" \"[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]\", [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], [[Fox News]], [[CNBC]], \"[[Inside Edition]],\" \"[[Tyra Banks Show]],\" \"Sally Jesse Show,\" \"[[Montel Williams]],\" \"[[Maury Povich Show]],\" \"Gayle King Show\" and the \"[[Howard Stern Show]].\"<ref name=\"99series\">{{cite book |title=99 things you wish you knew before-- your identity was stolen : your guide to protecting yourself from identity theft and computer fraud |date=2011-10-01 |publisher=The 99 Series 2011 |isbn=0983212295 |page=201 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13123022-99-things-you-wish-you-knew-before-your-identity-was-stolen}}</ref> In addition, he has been quoted in American news print publications such as ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', ''[[New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Boston Globe]]'', and ''Entrepreneur''.<ref name=\"99series\"/>\nSiciliano serves on the board of directors for the Identity Theft Resource Center<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lacey |first1=Charity |title=Robert Siciliano of IDTheftSecurity.com Joins ITRC Board of Directors |url=https://www.idtheftcenter.org/robert-siciliano-of-idtheftsecurity-com-joins-itrc-board-of-directors/ |website=Identity Theft Resource Center |accessdate=26 May 2019 |date=2 October 2014}}</ref> , contributes to the Realtor Safety Initiative Team for Realtor Safety Week<ref>{{cite web |title=Safety Resources for Associations and Brokerages |url=https://www.nar.realtor/safety/safety-resources-for-associations-and-brokerages |website=www.nar.realtor |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>, and is a regular keynote speaker at security related events.\n\n== Life and Career ==\nRobert Siciliano grew up in and around [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. Robert earned his certification in Private Investigations from Boston University, as well as his certificate as a Certified Speaking Professional from the NSA (National Speakers Association).<ref>{{cite web |title=The Switch to the Chip Card \u2013 One Year Later |url=https://newsroom.mastercard.com/people/robertsiciliano/ |website=MasterCard Social Newsroom |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> For the last 20+ years, Siciliano has been refining his rhetoric, content, message to carry out his  mission of informing the public on the issues and solutions surrounding security issues.<ref name=\"99series\"/> \n\nTalk show host [[Montel Williams]] was the first to broadcast Siciliano nationally.<ref name=\"99series\"/>  Show producers worked with Siciliano to develop scenarios where he would socially engineer his way into resident\u2019s homes in Elizabethtown New Jersey posing as a utility worker.<ref>{{cite news |title=Home safe home |url=https://www.sheknows.com/home-and-gardening/articles/7887/is-your-home-a-security-risk/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=SheKnows |date=17 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks]], Siciliano provided commentary as a news correspondent in regards to many security issues such as school shootings<ref>{{cite news |title=Homeland Security gives pointers on surviving shooting sprees {{!}} {{!}} dailyitem.com |url=https://www.dailyitem.com/homeland-security-gives-pointers-on-surviving-shooting-sprees/article_d75c3fed-db91-5556-b6a4-d2faf5cf1bb8.amp.html |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=www.dailyitem.com}}</ref>, terrorist hoaxes<ref>{{cite news |title=Anderson Cooper 'Swatted' as Celebrity 911 Hoax Hits East Coast |url=https://www.newsmax.com/thewire/anderson-cooper-swatted-celebrity-911-hoax/2013/05/08/id/503413/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Newsmax |date=8 May 2013}}</ref>, [[workplace violence]], privacy issues<ref>{{cite web |title=How the FBI Cracked the iPhone Case \u2026 With a Little Help From Outside |url=https://computer.howstuffworks.com/how-fbi-cracked-the-iphone-case.htm |website=HowStuffWorks |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en |date=7 April 2016}}</ref>, child abductions, and travel security.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Trends in Travel Security |url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/slideshows/new-trends-in-travel-security |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Travel + Leisure |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, lawyers representing the legendary rock band [[Led Zeppelin]] asked Robert Siciliano to surrender the domain www.ledzeppelin.com which he had owned for 5 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lieberman |first1=Allyson |title=WHAT\u2019S IN A NAME? A LAWSUIT \u2013 CELEBRITIES ARE MOVING IN ON WEBSITES BEARING THEIR NAMES |url=https://nypost.com/1999/10/15/whats-in-a-name-a-lawsuit-celebrities-are-moving-in-on-websites-bearing-their-names/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=New York Post |date=15 October 1999 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, Siciliano conducted an experiment that tested the ease of buying and deploying a retail ATM and as a result raised a few eyebrows in the ATM industry. He was able to purchase an ATM for $750.00 US on Craigslist.org, then program and deploy the retail ATM without any red tape or paperwork registration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leyden |first1=John |title=Second-hand ATM trade opens up fraud risk |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/11/18/second_hand_atm_fraud_risk/ |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=www.theregister.co.uk |date=2009-11-18 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2013, Siciliano ran the 117th edition of the mass-participation Boston Marathon as a charity runner for Boston Children's Hospital. Roberts experience during the bombing was chronicled by the Boston Globe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Teitell |first1=Beth |title=Some agonize over fleeing Marathon bombing scene |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/style/2013/05/08/boston-marathon-heroes-are-lauded-some-who-didn-rush-help-grapple-with-guilt/SNUKlSFLDMKTmz3Sen69dP/story.html |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=2013-05-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Keynotes ===\n\n* The Western States Director Education Foundation Symposium<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsdef.org/pastagendas.cfm|title=Western States Director Education Foundation|date=2005-11-01|publisher=WSDEF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011103150/http://www.wsdef.org/pastagendas.cfm|archivedate=2008-10-11|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* National Association of Credit Managers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacmchicago.org/omaha/home_omaha.htm|title=NACM Midwest|date=2007-04-19|publisher=Nacmchicago.org|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Massachusetts Association of Realtors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marealtor.net/conv/schedule.htm|title=Conference Schedule|date=|publisher=Marealtor.net|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Industrial Asset Management Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamc.org/pressSept2004.shtml|title=Industrial Asset Management Council|publisher=IAMC|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613063040/http://iamc.org/pressSept2004.shtml|archivedate=2010-06-13|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Meetings Professionals International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpiweb.org/CMS/mpiweb/mpicontent.aspx?id=16434|title=Meeting Professionals International|publisher=Mpiweb.org|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120903200118/http://www.mpiweb.org/CMS/mpiweb/mpicontent.aspx?id=16434|archive-date=2012-09-03|url-status=dead|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Louisiana State University<ref>[http://www.lsu.edu/safety/pdfs/Safety_Programs.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060902213629/http://www.lsu.edu/safety/pdfs/Safety_Programs.pdf|date=September 2, 2006}}</ref>\n*United Bankers Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/crime-law-enforcement-corrections/criminal-offenses-fraud/11706822-1.html|title=Bankers' bank event focuses on tech security, ID theft &#124; North America > United States from|date=|publisher=AllBusiness.com|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n* Tools of the Trade REALTOR Expo<ref>{{cite news |title=Get Your Game On at Realcomp\u2019s Tools Expo by Attending Robert Siciliano\u2019s Presentation\u2026 |url=https://realcomp.moveinmichigan.com/News-Events/Feature-2018/April-2018/Robert_Siciliano_Get_Your_Game_On |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=realcomp.moveinmichigan.com}}</ref>\n* Parady Financial<ref>{{cite web |title=Protect Your Wealth Summit October |url=https://www.paradyfinancial.com/protectyourwealthoctober/ |website=Parady Financial |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n* National Association of Realtors<ref>{{cite news |title=Realtors Highlight the Importance of Defending Against a Data Breach |url=http://athensceo.com/news/2018/11/realtors-highlight-importance-defending-against-data-breach/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Athens CEO |language=en}}</ref>\n* Michigan Credit Union League<ref>{{cite news |title=Identity Theft Big Topic at Fall Leadership Development Conference |url=https://www.mcul.org/News?article_id=28113 |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Michigan Credit Union League}}</ref>\n* Global Business Travel Association<ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago BTA Q1 2015 Chapter Meeting |url=https://chicagobta.org/meetinginfo.php?id=23&ts=1423500415 |website=Chicago Business Travel Association |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Realtors Triple Play<ref>{{cite news |title=Agent & Client ID Theft Security & Awareness \u2013 Triple Play REALTOR\u00ae Convention & Trade Expo |url=https://www.realtorstripleplay.com/tripleplay-sessions/2018/agent-client-id-theft-security-awareness/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Realtors Triple Play}}</ref>\n\n==Books Authored==\nSiciliano is the author of 5 books:\n\n# Siciliano, Robert. The Safety Minute: How To Be Safe In The Streets At Home And Abroad So You Can Save Your Life! 1996. SafetyZone Press. Boston, MA. {{ISBN|0-9648126-2-2}}\n# Siciliano, Robert. The Safety Minute: Living On High Alert; How To Take Control Of Your Personal Security And Prevent Fraud. 2003. SafetyZone Press. Boston, MA. {{ISBN|0-9648126-7-3}}\n# Siciliano, Robert. 99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Identity Was Stolen. 2011. McAfee. Florida, NY. {{ASIN|B0060GBP8Y}}<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year= |title=99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Identity Was Stolen |publisher=Amazon |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.amazon.com/Things-Before-Identity-Stolen-ebook/dp/B0060GBP8Y |accessdate=September 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n# Siciliano, Robert. 99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Mobile Device Was Hacked. 2012. McAfee. Florida, NY. {{ISBN|1937801195}}<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year= |title=99 Things You Wish You Knew Before Your Mobile Device Was Hacked |publisher=Amazon |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.amazon.com/Things-Before-Mobile-Device-Hacked/dp/1937801195/ref=sr_1_5?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1347128068&sr=1-5 |accessdate=September 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n#Siciliano, Robert. Identity Theft Privacy. 2018. Tross Consulting. Tempe, AZ. {{ISBN|978-0-9969500-8-4}}. \n\nHe has also contributed to the development of five other books, including ones such as '' Protect your business against threats internally and externally''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Friedmann |first1=Susan |title=Riches in Niches: How to Make It Big in a Small Market: Easy Read Comfort Edition |date=2009 |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |isbn=9781442956933 |page=143 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqHiz7C7_i4C&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=%22robert+siciliano%22+Riches+In+Niches&source=bl&ots=gSgMzdJ85R&sig=ACfU3U0Gv0_CzOsUDznv0I75IcQg7qIzbg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3xYmj06_iAhVBTd8KHVyRBjkQ6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22robert%20siciliano%22%20Riches%20In%20Niches&f=false |accessdate=26 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and ''Riches In Niches, How to make it big in a small market''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Friedmann |first1=Susan |title=Riches in Niches: How to Make It Big in a Small Market: Easy Read Comfort Edition |date=2009 |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |isbn=9781442956933 |page=143 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqHiz7C7_i4C&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=%22robert+siciliano%22+%22Riches+In+Niches%22&source=bl&ots=gShEzbH56Q&sig=ACfU3U1zwdKjDObMuErdyyqBNI0M7myEsA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQrI7omuniAhUEIqwKHWc9DXgQ6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22robert%20siciliano%22%20%22Riches%20In%20Niches%22&f=false |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://safr.me/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2892079}}\n\n===Appearances in media===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www1.whdh.com/features/articles/uncovers/BO130883/ |title=Counterfeit cash machines |publisher=whdh.com |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2010-03-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928201758/http://www1.whdh.com/features/articles/uncovers/BO130883/ |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,464794,00.html |title=Internet Scams Targeting Growing Out of Work Population |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-siciliano/social-media-messages-tel_b_484698.html |title=Social Media Messages Telling Too Much? |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=2010-03-03 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siciliano, Robert}}\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American male actors]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: , ''New York Times'', \u2192 , ''The New York Times'',,  and Career \u2192  and career, Authored \u2192 authored,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, italicss, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Siciliano"}
{"title_page": "Belgian Congo in World War II", "text_new": "[[File:Belgian Congo Leopoldville square.jpg|thumb|A busy city square in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], capital of the Belgian Congo, 1943|275px]]\n\nThe involvement of the [[Belgian Congo]] (the modern-day [[Democratic Republic of Congo]]) in [[World War II]] began with the German invasion of Belgium in May 1940. Despite Belgium's surrender, the Congo remained in the conflict on the [[Allies (World War II)|Allied side]], administered by the [[Belgian government in exile]], and provided much-needed raw materials, most notably [[uranium]], to the United Kingdom and the United States.\n\nCongolese troops of the [[Force Publique]] fought alongside British forces in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]], and a Congolese medical unit served in [[Battle of Madagascar|Madagascar]] and in the [[Burma Campaign]]. Congolese formations also acted as garrisons in [[Kingdom of Egypt|Egypt]], [[Colony and Protectorate of Nigeria|Nigeria]] and [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]].\n\nThe increasing demands placed on the Congolese population by the colonial authorities during the war, however, provoked strikes, riots and other forms of resistance, particularly from the indigenous Congolese. These were repressed, often violently, by the Belgian colonial authorities. The Congo's comparative prosperity during the conflict led to a wave of post-war immigration from Belgium, bringing the white population to 100,000 by 1950, as well as a period of industrialisation that continued throughout the 1950s. The role played by Congolese uranium during the hostilities caused the country to be of interest to the [[Soviet Union]] during the [[Cold War]].\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Battle of Belgium|German occupation of Belgium during World War II}}\n[[File:Monument Albert Kinshasa 5.JPG|thumb|Colonial officials, including the Governor-General, [[Pierre Ryckmans (Governor-General)|Pierre Ryckmans]], in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] in 1938.]]\n\nFollowing World War I, Belgium possessed two colonies in Africa: the [[Belgian Congo]], which it had controlled since its annexation of the [[Congo Free State]] in 1908, and [[Ruanda-Urundi]], a former German colony that had been mandated to Belgium in 1924 by the [[League of Nations]].<ref name=Larousse1>{{cite web|title=Empire Colonial Belge|url=http://www.larousse.fr/encyclopedie/autre-region/Empire_colonial_belge/182725|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions Larousse]]|work=Online Encyclopedia|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> The Belgian colonial military numbered 18,000 soldiers, making it one of the largest standing colonial armies in Africa at the time.<ref name=Killingray7>{{cite book|last=Killingray|first=David|title=Fighting for Britain: African soldiers in the Second World War|year=2010|publisher=James Currey|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-84701-015-5|page=7}}</ref> The Congo underwent an economic boom in the 1920s and mines, plantations, and transportation networks were greatly developed. The [[Great Depression]] led to a collapse of commodity prices, undermining the colony's export-based economy and leading to a large reduction in income and employment. The only industry that expanded during the time period was centered around [[cotton]] production.<ref>{{cite journal| last = G\u00e9rard-Libois| first = Jules| last2 = Verhaegen| first2 = Beno\u00eet| title = Le Congo: Du domaine de L\u00e9opold II \u00e0 l\u2019ind\u00e9pendance| journal =  Courrier hebdomadaire du CRISP| issue = 1077| pages = 1\u201334| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| date = 26 April 1985| language = French| url = https://www.cairn.info/revue-courrier-hebdomadaire-du-crisp-1985-12-page-1.htm| doi = 10.3917/cris.1077.0001}}</ref>\n\nThe Belgian government followed a policy of neutrality during the interwar years. [[Nazi Germany]] invaded Belgium on 10 May 1940 which, after [[Battle of Belgium|18 days of fighting]], surrendered and was [[German occupation of Belgium during World War II|occupied]] by German forces. [[Leopold III of Belgium|King Leopold III]], who had surrendered to the Germans, was kept a prisoner for the rest of the war.<ref name=Yapou1>{{cite book|last=Yapou|first=Eliezer|title=Governments in Exile, 1939\u20131945|year=1998|location=Jerusalem|url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapoubelgium.html|chapter=4: Belgium: Disintegration and Resurrection}}</ref> Just before the fall of Belgium, its government, including the Minister of the Colonies, [[Albert de Vleeschauwer]], fled to [[Bordeaux]] in France.<ref name=Yapou1/>\n\n== Entry of the Congo into the war ==\nOn 10 May 1940 Belgian officials formally requested that the United Kingdom and France declare their respect for the Congo's neutrality and support for its territorial integrity in a future peace settlement. The British government refused, wanting to ensure that the Congo would not fall under German control, and France followed suit. The French government briefly considered sending troops to occupy [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], the Congolese capital.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=122}} On the day of the Belgian Army's surrender, the British government, uncertain about what would happen to the territory, held a crisis meeting in London. The [[Admiralty]] proposed sending troops to occupy strategic locations in the Congo, but this was quickly ruled unfeasible due to other military commitments. The British government then resolved that if the Belgian government collapsed, it would support an \"independent\" Congo.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=125\u2013126}}\n\nWithin the Congo itself, opinion was divided on whether or not to continue to support the war. Belgian corporate officials hoped that the colony would take a neutral stance, and the staff of the [[Force Publique]], the colonial army, recommended a declaration of neutrality or even independence under the authority of the [[List of colonial governors of the Congo Free State and Belgian Congo|Governor-General of the Congo]], [[Pierre Ryckmans (Governor-General)|Pierre Ryckmans]]. Ryckmans refused to take this advice,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=127}} and declared on the day of the Belgian Army's surrender that the colony would remain loyal to the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]].<ref name=Urome>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=L'Histoire du Congo vue par les Coloniaux|publisher=Urome.be|url=http://www.urome.be/pdf/fhisconbe.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref> Despite this assurance, disruption broke out in the city of [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]] (now Kisangani in the eastern Congo) among the white population panicking about the future of the colony and the threat of an Italian invasion.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nOn 17 June France declared an armistice with Germany. Though Ryckmans had declared that he would continue to support the Allied cause, the Belgian government in Bordeaux was deeply disheartened by the French surrender.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=72, 231}} Prime Minister [[Hubert Pierlot]] believed that it lacked the resources to continue to fight and thus it would be better to negotiate a peace with Germany instead of going into exile in the United Kingdom. Most of the ministers agreed, though de Vleeschauwer dissented. While the government prepared to negotiate with Germany, representatives of various Belgo-Congolese companies in Bordeaux informed the ministers of rumours that should Belgium surrender, the United Kingdom would seize control of the Congo.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=72\u201373}} Meanwhile, some circles in occupied Belgium feared that if the Congo aligned itself with the Allies it would be permanently lost as a colony to Belgium. In Brussels, the Germans established a \"Kolonial Politisches B\u00fcro\" that attempted to forge connections with what remained of the Ministry of Colonies.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=124\u2013125}}\n\nThe British were determined that the Congo should not fall into Axis hands, and planned to invade and occupy the colony if the Belgians did not come to an arrangement. This was particularly because the Allies were desperate for raw materials like [[natural rubber|rubber]] which the Congo could produce in abundance.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} On 20 June the British Foreign Secretary told the Belgian ambassador in London that the United Kingdom would not accept German dominance over the colony.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=231}} Meanwhile, the Belgo-Congolese businessmen proposed that de Vleeschauwer go to London to ensure that Belgian sovereignty over the Congo would be respected. Pierlot suggested that de Vleeschauwer should be granted the new title of Administrator-general of the Congo, allowing him to pursue this cause even if the government later collapsed and his ministerial mandate became void.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=73\u201374, 232}}  The government agreed to the idea, and on 18 June it passed a law-decree, granting de Vleeschauwer the title and conferring on him full legislative and executive power to manage the Congo. The decree also stipulated that in the event the administrator-general was unable to exercise his duties, the responsibility would be passed on to the governor-general.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=123, 132}}\n\nDe Vleeschauwer departed for London, arriving on 4 July.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=73\u201374, 232}} He spoke with members of the British government and assured them that he would place all of the Congo's raw materials at the disposal of the United Kingdom's war effort. Over the following months Pierlot and two other ministers managed to reach London while the rest declared their intention to remain in France and resign. In October Pierlot, de Vleeschauwer, and the two other ministers officially established the [[Belgian government in exile]], recognised by the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=232\u2013233}} Despite his presence, de Vleeschauwer was politically marginalised by Finance Minister [[Camille Gutt]] and played little role thereafter in the government.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=237\u2013238}} There was also conflict between de Vleeschauwer, who wanted to assure his own authority over the Congo, and Foreign Minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] who sought to be more conciliatory with regard to Allied influence in the colony.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=131}}\n\nThe Germans were upset by the Congo's support for the Allies, and threatened to apply sanctions to Belgian colonial enterprises. Leopold III expressed his discontent with Ryckman's decisions, believing that the colony should remain neutral.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=128}} Royalist politicians sent messages to the Belgian authorities in London, attempting to dissuade them from allowing the Congo to support the British war effort. In October 1940 Leopold III requested permission from Nazi German leader [[Adolf Hitler]] to dispatch an emissary to L\u00e9opoldville to persuade the colonial administration to assume neutrality, but the trip was never authorised.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=128\u2013129}}\n\n==Economic contribution==\n=== Allied support ===\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote=\"The Belgian Congo has entered the service of the Allies. Its economic doctrine and practices have been rapidly adapted to the new conditions and, whilst everything is being done to maintain the potentiality of the Congo wealth, there is no hesitation whatsoever when it comes to sacrificing any riches in favor of the war effort.\"|2=[[Albert de Vleeschauwer]], Minister of the Colonies, 1942<ref name=TBCAW1>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=3|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Pilot Officer H. A. Picard of No. 350 (Belgian) Squadron, on the wing of his Spitfire at Kenley, July 1942. CH6356.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A Belgian pilot in the British [[Royal Air Force]], 1942. His [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] aircraft was funded by contributions from the Congo, and took its name, \"Luvungi\", from [[Luvungi|the Congolese town]] of that name.]]\nSoon after the establishment of the Belgian government in exile in London, negotiations began between the Belgians and the British about the role which the Congo would play in the Allied war effort.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} The two parties came to an arrangement on 21 January 1941, in which all the British demands were accepted, including a 30 percent [[devaluation]] of the [[Congolese franc]] and the entrance of the Congo into the [[sterling area]].{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}}{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=235}} With the official agreement and the Congolese declaration of support for the Allies, the economy of the Congo\u2014in particular its production of important raw materials\u2014was placed at the disposal of the Allies.<ref name=TBCAW1/> Though Ryckmans and leaders of the [[Banque du Congo Belge]] (the Congo's [[central bank]]) were pleased at the entry into the sterling area, which guaranteed an export market for the territory, they strongly disliked the fixed prices the agreement entailed which were favourable to the United Kingdom and worried that only trading with sterling could negatively impact the Congo's [[foreign exchange reserves]]. Business leaders in the colony were disgruntled as well, and boosted production of goods not mentioned in the agreement to sell to the neutral United States at their standard market value.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=235}} In 1942, after the United States joined the Allies, the Belgian government negotiated a new economic agreement with the United States and United Kingdom. Belgian officials never signed it, but it was ''de facto'' applied for the rest of the war,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=130}} and Congolese trade remained directed at the two countries.<ref name=TBCAW1/> The Congo's economic output became an even more valuable asset to the Allies after Japan occupied large swathes of South East Asia in 1942, halting those areas' exports of key tropical commodities such as rubber.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}}\n\n[[File:Sheets of copper from Katanga mines, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Sheets of copper from the [[Katanga Province]]'s mines]]\n\nThe Congo had become increasingly centralised economically during the Great Depression of the 1930s, as the Belgian government encouraged the production there of cotton, which had value on the international market.<ref name=Larousse1/> The greatest economic demands on the Congo during the war were related to raw materials. Between 1938 and 1944, the number of workers employed in the mines of the ''[[Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga]]'' (UMHK) rose from 25,000 to 49,000 to cope with the increased demand.<ref name=Zeilig66>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=66}}</ref> The colonial administration enacted ultimately successful policies aimed at increasing the size of the Congo's labour force; the number of wage labourers in the colony grew from 480,000 in 1938 to 800,000 in 1945.{{sfn|Martin|1985|p=423}} In order to increase production for the war effort, the colonial authorities increased the hours and the speed at which workers, both European and African, were expected to work. This led to increasing [[labour unrest]] across the colony.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} [[Forced labour]], which had been banned in the 1930s, was reintroduced to keep up with demand; by 1944, the maximum number of days of forced labour per year was raised to 120 for rural Congolese.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=99}} Discontent among the white population was also increased by the raising of heavy war taxes, which sometimes reached as high as 40 percent.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} High taxes and price controls were enforced from 1941, limiting the amount of profit that could be made and curbing [[War profiteering|profiteering]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=8|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> While the price controls aided exports to the Allies, it adversely affected Congolese peasants, who earned less despite their increased amount of labour.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=99}}\n\nThe vast majority of the Congolese-produced raw resources were exported to other Allied countries. According to the Belgian government, by 1942 the entire colony's output of [[copper]] and [[palm oil]] were being exported to the United Kingdom, while almost all the colony's lumber was sent to South Africa.<ref name=BCAW11>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=11|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> Exports to the United States also rose from [[United States Dollar|$]]600,000 in early 1940 to $2,700,000 by 1942.<ref name=BCAW12>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=12|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> Despite the Allied cooperation, many officials of the colonial administration treated American and British diplomats with suspicion, fearing the potential economic rivalry posed by their countries to Belgian enterprises.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}\n\nAs per a deal reached on 21 March 1941, loans from the Banque du Congo Belge enabled the Belgian government in exile and [[Free Belgian Forces]] to fund themselves, unlike most other states in exile, which operated through subsidies and donations from sympathetic governments.<ref name=Zeilig66/>{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=236\u2013237}} It also meant that the Belgian gold reserves, which had been moved to London in 1940, were not needed to fund the war effort, and therefore were still available at the end of the war.<ref name=Zeilig66/>\n\n===Uranium===\n[[Uranium-235]] was mined in the Congo at [[Shinkolobwe]] in [[Katanga Province|Katanga]] before the war by the UMHK for export to Belgium. It was originally used by the medical industry, for radium production, and for coloring ceramics. Scientists in Europe later discovered that enriched uranium could be used in the production of a supposed [[atomic bomb]]. When physicist [[Albert Einstein]] wrote U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt to warn him of the possibility of a German atomic bomb program, he advised him that the Congo was a main source of the mineral.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=83}} Uranium extracted from the disused Shinkolobwe mine ultimately proved instrumental in the development of an atomic bomb during the Allied [[Manhattan Project]]. The director of UMHK, [[Edgar Sengier]], secretly dispatched half of its uranium stock to [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1940; in September 1942, he sold it to the [[United States Army]].<ref>{{cite news |first=William J. |last=Broad |authorlink= |title=Why They Called It the Manhattan Project |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/30/science/30manh.html|work=[[New York Times]] |date=30 October 2007 |accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nSengier himself moved to [[New York (state)|New York]], from where he directed the UMHK's operations for the rest of the war.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael|last=Pollack |authorlink= |title=Answers to Questions About New York City|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/27/nyregion/27fyi.html |work=[[New York Times]]|date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref> The U.S. government sent soldiers from the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] to Shinkolobwe in 1942 to restore the mine and improve its transport links by renovating the local aerodromes and port facilities.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hunt|first=Margaret R.|title=Manhattan-Uranium Connection sidenotes|url=http://www3.amherst.edu/~mrhunt/uranium/notes8.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060918220848/http://www.amherst.edu/~mrhunt/uranium/notes8.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 September 2006|publisher=Amherst College|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> In September 1944 the Belgian government reached an agreement with the United Kingdom and the United States, whereby it would sell only those two countries the Congolese uranium at a fixed price.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=134}} That year the Americans acquired a further {{convert|1720|LT}} of Uranium ore from the newly reopened mine.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Oscar E.|last2=Hewlett|first2=Richard G.|authorlink2=Richard G. Hewlett|title=The New World, 1939\u20131946|year=1990|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, Calif.|url=https://www.governmentattic.org/5docs/TheNewWorld1939-1946.pdf|format=PDF|isbn=0-520-07186-7|edition=Reprint|pages=285\u2013288}}</ref>\n\n=== German diamond trafficking ===\nDuring the war there were frequent rumors that some Belgian industrialists involved in colonial enterprises were covertly aiding Germany.{{sfn|Williams|2018|pp=49\u201350}} American officials found working with Belgo-Congolese mining companies to secure [[industrial diamonds]] to be difficult.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}} According to the Belgian government, by 1942 the entire colony's output of industrial diamonds was being shipped to the United Kingdom.<ref name=BCAW11/> In reality, many industrial diamonds were smuggled to Nazi Germany for use in the German war effort. Most Congolese diamonds were mined by [[Formini\u00e8re]], a subsidiary of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Belgique]], which was in turn a member of the [[De Beers]] Diamond Syndicate. In 1940, the Syndicate reported that the Congo annually produced 10.9 million carats of diamonds. Immediately after the outbreak of war reported production sharply declined, and by 1942 production had officially fallen to 5 million carats\u2013roughly the original production number minus the amount exported to Germany before the war. Believing that a large volume of diamonds were being smuggled out of the colony, American intelligence officials convinced British agents to inspect the security of the mines. The officer tasked with overseeing the inspection teams concluded that proper security measures were lacking and that Formini\u00e8re and [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 mini\u00e8re de Beceka]] personnel fostered a \"sinister atmosphere\" during the tours.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}} Firmin van Bree, the director of Formini\u00e8re, was widely suspected of maintaining German sympathies.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}{{sfn|Williams|2018|p=50}} The German government conducted secret negotiations with leaders of Formini\u00e8re and the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale, and reached deals that allowed them to purchase large quantities of diamonds until 1944. In 1943 Germany paid the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale $10.5 million for diamonds. American and British agents ultimately uncovered a wide smuggling network that brought diamonds out of the Congo and to German-occupied Europe by air and sea. Proposals by the Americans to stifle the illicit trade were dissuaded by the British [[Ministry of Economic Warfare]], whose Diamond Committee was dominated by members of the De Beers Diamond Syndicate. After the end of the war the Belgian government demanded that Germany pay $25 million owed to the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale for 576,676 carats of diamonds.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}\n\n==Military involvement==\n=== Force Publique ===\n[[File:Belgian Congo enlisting for the Force Publique.jpg|thumb|275px|Congolese enlisting in the Force Publique following the outbreak of war]]\nThe [[Force Publique]] (or \"Public Force\") was the combined police and military force of both the Congo and Ruanda-Urundi. During World War II, it constituted the bulk of the [[Free Belgian Forces]],<ref name=Killingray7/> numbering over 40,000 men at its peak in 1943.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=98}} Like other colonial armies of the time, the Force Publique was racially segregated;{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=62}} it was led by 280 white officers and NCOs, but otherwise comprised indigenous black Africans.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buzin|first=Jean|title=The \"Belgian Congo Air Force.\" The Air Force that Never Was&nbsp;... |journal=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Royale des Pionniers et Anciens de l'Aviation Belge|url=http://www.vieillestiges.be/files/articles/belgiancongoairforce_fr.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> The Force Publique had never received the more modern equipment supplied to the [[Belgian Armed Forces]] before the war, and so had to use outdated weapons and equipment like the [[Stokes mortar]] and the [[70 mm St Chamond mountain howitzer|Saint Chamond 70&nbsp;mm howitzer]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bellis|first=Malcolm A.|title=Commonwealth Divisions: 1939\u20131945|year=1999|publisher=Selbstverl.|location=Crewe|isbn=0-9529693-0-0|edition=1st|page=45}}</ref> During the war the force was expanded through recruitment and the calling up of reserves.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=98}}\n\n===East African Campaign===\n{{main|East African Campaign (World War II)}}\n\nWhile willing to mobilise the Congo's economic resources for the Allied war effort, the Belgian government in exile was initially much more hesitant to deploy Congolese troops in combat. The government also refused to declare war on Germany's ally, Italy, which had colonies in Africa and was fighting to secure British possessions in the continent,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=126, 128\u2013129}} because the Belgian royal family had dynastic links with the Italian royal family. This attitude changed after it became known that Italian aircraft based in occupied Belgium were attacking Britain and when an Italian submarine sank a Belgian cargo ship. A Belgian declaration of war was eventually delivered against Italy on 23 November 1940.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=84}} Two days later, Ryckmans proclaimed that a state of war existed between Italy and the Congo.{{sfn|Weller|1942|p=5}}\n\n[[File:Force Publique leaving for Ethiopia.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Force Publique]] soldiers leaving the Congo to participate in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]] in Ethiopia|left]]\nThree brigades of the Force Publique were sent to [[Italian East Africa]] alongside British forces to fight the Italians.<ref name=Yapou1/> The Belgian 1st Colonial Brigade operated in the Galla-Sidamo area in the South-West sector.<ref name=\"Ready 1985 45\">{{cite book|last=Ready|first=J. Lee|title=Forgotten Allies: the Military Contribution of the Colonies, Exiled Governments, and Lesser Powers to the Allied Victory in World War II|year=1985|publisher=Mcfarland|location=Jefferson|volume=I|isbn=0-7864-7168-9|page=45}}</ref> In May 1941, around 8,000 men of the Force Publique, under Major-General [[Auguste-\u00c9douard Gilliaert]], successfully [[Siege of Sa\u00efo|cut off]] the retreat of General [[Pietro Gazzera]]'s Italians at [[Dembidolo|Sa\u00efo]], in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] after marching over {{convert|1,000|km}} from their bases in western Congo. The troops suffered from [[malaria]] and other tropical diseases, but successfully defeated the Italians in a number of engagements.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}} Gilliaert subsequently accepted the surrender of Gazzera and 7,000 Italian troops.<ref name=\"Ready 1985 45\"/> Over the course of the campaign in Ethiopia, the Force Publique received the surrender of nine Italian generals, 370 high-ranking officers and 15,000 Italian colonial troops before the end of 1941.{{sfn|Weller|1942|p=3}} The Congolese forces in Ethiopia suffered about 500 fatalities.<ref name=Killingray7/>\n\nAfter the Allied victory in Ethiopia, the Force Publique moved to the British colony of Nigeria, which was being used as a staging ground for a planned invasion of [[French Dahomey|Vichy-controlled Dahomey]] which did not occur,{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}} was also garrisoned by 13,000 Congolese troops.<ref name=Killingray7/> Then a part of the Force Publique went to [[Kingdom of Egypt|Egypt]] and British [[Mandatory Palestine]] and was redesignated the 1st Belgian Congo Brigade Group during 1943 and 1944.<ref name=Thomas17>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|title=Foreign Volunteers of the Allied Forces, 1939\u201345|year=1991|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-85532-136-6|page=17}}</ref>\n\n===Medical support===\nA medical unit from the Congo, the 10th (Belgian Congo) [[Casualty Clearing Station]], was formed in 1943, and served alongside British forces during the [[Battle of Madagascar|invasion of Madagascar]] and in the Far East during the [[Burma Campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Epilogue Oriental|url=http://www.mil.be/vox/subject/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=612&MENU=916&PAGE=2|accessdate=2 July 2013|newspaper=VOX|date=16 June 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209023739/http://www.mil.be/vox/subject/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=612&MENU=916&PAGE=2|archivedate=9 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The unit (which had a small body of Force Publique troops for local defense of the station) included 350 black and 20 white personnel, and continued to serve with the British until 1945.<ref>{{cite web|title=Burma: The 10th Belgian Congo Casualty Clearing Station, 1945|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205058818|publisher=[[Imperial War Museum]]|accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life in the Belgian Congo==\n[[File:Belgian Congo houses built for Congolese workers.jpg|thumb|Congolese worker housing, c. 1943]]\nAt the start of the war, the population of the Congo numbered approximately 12&nbsp;million black people and 30,000 whites.<ref>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=65|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> The colonial government segregated the population along racial lines and there was very little mixing between the colours.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lagae|first=Johan|title=Rewriting Congo's Colonial Past: History, Memory, and Colonial Built Heritage in Lubumbashi, Democratic Republic of the Congo|year=2005|publisher=Institut national d'histoire et d'art|location=Paris|url=http://inha.revues.org/499#text|chapter=The built fabric of a segregated city}}</ref> The white population was highly urbanized and, in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], lived in [[Gombe, Kinshasa|a quarter]] of the city separated from the black majority. All blacks in the city had to adhere to a [[curfew]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Njoh|first=Ambe J.|title=Planning Power: Social Control and Planning in Colonial Africa|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=1-84472-160-4|page=217}}</ref> The colonial authorities arrested [[enemy alien]]s in the Congo and confiscated their property in 1940.<ref name=bic7>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=7|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> The colonial administration tried to conceal the war from the African population by censoring the media, but the Congolese noticed the internal tensions among the white population and the detention of German and Italian nationals.{{sfn|Geenen|2019|p=114}} To better counter external influences in the colony, the administration established a Bureau of Information and Propaganda.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=102}}\n\nThe demands of the colonial administration fell hardest on rural residents, which were conscripted for road construction projects and rubber harvesting. Conditions were harsh for the labourers, and in some cases were conflated in the Congolese [[collective memory]] with the earlier atrocities committed by the Congo Free State in relation to [[Atrocities in the Congo Free State#Red Rubber system and forced labour|its rubber collection system]].{{sfn|Martin|1985|p=423}} The urbanised Congolese generally experienced more financial gain during the war than their rural counterparts, though several workers who had collected large amounts of rubber earned even more money.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} During the war the Belgian government in exile directed propaganda at the Allied states that created a positive image of its colony in an attempt to legitimise its rule. In [[New York City]], the Belgian Information Center released numerous publications which asserted that the Belgians had rescued the Congolese from \"terrible conditions\" and improved life in the territory.{{sfn|Stanard|2014|p=98}} Wider Allied propaganda also downplayed internal political tensions within the Congo and in its relations with the Belgian government so as to portray the coordination of its war effort in a harmonious fashion.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=130}}\n\nEducation was overwhelmingly controlled by Protestant and Catholic missions, which were also responsible for providing limited welfare support to the rural Congolese.<ref name=BCAW11/> The occupation of Belgium severed Belgian missionaries from their parent organisations, causing the colonial administration to subsidise their activities to make up for budget deficits. The war did not adversely impact their evangelising, and the number of reported baptisms conducted increased from 1,824,000 in 1939 to a cumulative total of 2,214,000 in 1942.<ref>{{cite news| title = Activity of the Social Services in the Belgian Congo in the War| newspaper = News From Belgium| volume = IV| issue = 22| date = 3 June 1944| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERbPAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> Healthcare was provided by a mix of government and corporate physicians, private practitioners, and missionaries. At the outbreak of the war there were 302 doctors working in the Congo. Some medical personnel accompanied the Force Publique on its foreign deployments, but the vast majority remained in the colony for the conflict's duration. Unlike the neighboring French possessions, the war did not adversely affect the resources of healthcare providers in the Congo. Medical research continued and a new journal was created so that findings could be published while the territory was separated from Belgium.{{sfn|Pepin|2011|p=145}}\n\nFood remained unrationed during the war, with only the sales of tires and automobiles restricted by the government.<ref name=BCAW11/> Nevertheless, the war did lead to a shortage of consumer goods.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} The devaluation of the Congolese franc also made foreign imports more expensive.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} One of the consequences of the Congo's economic mobilisation during the war, particularly for the black population, was significant [[urbanisation]]. Just 9% of the indigenous population lived in cities in 1938; by 1950, the figure stood at close to 20%.<ref name=IS1/> The colonial government also greatly improved transport and production facilities during the war.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}}\n\n==Unrest==\n\n===Strikes===\n[[File:Katanga mine worker, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Katangese miner]]\nThe demands made by the colonial government on Congolese workers during the war provoked strikes and riots from the workforce. Whites in the colony were allowed to form [[trade union]]s for the first time during the war, and their demands for better pay and working conditions were often emulated by black workers.<ref name= higginson/> A lack of European skilled labor forced the colonial government to train and give native Congolese skilled labor positions for the first time, but they were paid less than their white colleagues, generating discontent.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} In October 1941, white workers in the colony unsuccessfully attempted a [[general strike]] across the colony.<ref name= higginson>{{cite book|last=Higginson|first=John|title=A Working Class in the Making: Belgian Colonial Labor Policy, Private Enterprise, and the African Mineworker, 1907\u20131951|year=1989|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wis.|isbn=0-299-12070-8|page=188|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote=\"Why should a white man be paid more than a black, when all the white man does is stand there, giving orders, his arms behind his back and with his pipe in his mouth? We should take our rights, or we won't work tomorrow.\"|2=L\u00e9onard Mpoyi, December 1941<ref name=Zeilig68/>}}\nIn December 1941, black mine workers at various sites in [[Katanga Province]], including [[Likasi|Jadotville]] and [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], went on strike, demanding that their pay be increased from 1.50 [[Congolese franc|francs]] to 2 francs to compensate for rising living costs.<ref name=Murindwa14>{{cite book|last=Rutanga|first=Murindwa|title=Politics, Religion and Power in the Great Lakes Region|year=2011|publisher=Council for the Development of Social Science Research in Africa (CODESRIA)|location=Dakar|isbn=2-86978-492-9|page=14}}</ref><ref name=BBC1>{{cite web|title=The Story of Africa: World War II|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1624_story_of_africa/page20.shtml|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 July 2013}}</ref> The strike started on 3 December, and by the next day 1,400 workers had downed tools.<ref>{{cite book|last=Higginson|first=John|title=A Working Class in the Making: Belgian Colonial Labor Policy, Private Enterprise, and the African Mineworker, 1907\u20131951|year=1989|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wis.|isbn=0-299-12070-8|page=189|edition=1st}}</ref> All UMHK sites were affected by 9 December.<ref name=Zeilig68>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=68}}</ref> The strike was also fueled by other grievances against the colonial order and segregation.{{citation needed|date= April 2020}} \n\n[[File:Elizabethville Massacre (Matulu).jpg|thumb|A painting of the \u00c9lisabethville massacre by [[Tshibumba Kanda-Matulu]], a Congolese artist, depicting the church and colonial state (personified at the right) as the instigators]]\nFrom the start, the colonial authorities attempted to persuade the strikers to disperse and go back to work. When they refused, they were fired on. In Jadotville, 15 strikers were shot dead by the military.<ref name=\"Zeilig68\"/> In \u00c9lisabethville, the strikers, including their leader L\u00e9onard Mpoyi, were invited to negotiations at the town's stadium, where they were offered various concessions, including a 30% pay rise.<ref name=Zeilig68/> When the workers refused, the Governor of Katanga, Amour Maron, shot Mpoyi, killing him. The Governor then ordered his soldiers to fire on the other strikers in the stadium.<ref name=Zeilig69>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=69}}</ref> Between 60 and 70 strikers were killed during the protest,<ref name=BBC1/><ref>{{cite news|last=Mobe|first=Anicet|title=L'arm\u00e9e au Congo&nbsp;... |url=http://www.lalibre.be/debats/opinions/l-armee-au-congo-51b8d872e4b0de6db9c2b32a|accessdate=8 August 2013|newspaper=[[La Libre Belgique]]|date=18 August 2011}}</ref> although the official estimate was around 30.<ref>Transcription of the proceedings of the Council of Ministers of the government in exile, 18 December 1941, reproduced in {{cite web|title=Gr\u00e8ve \u00e0 L'Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga|url=http://www.expocongo.be/content.php?m=6&r=4&doc=218&l=fr|publisher=Expo Congo|accessdate=8 August 2013}}</ref> The miners returned to work on 10 December.<ref name=Zeilig69/>\n\nNumerous smaller strikes occurred in the Congo later in the war, though not on the same scale as in 1941. In 1944 strikes broke out in Katanga and [[Kasai region|Kasa\u00ef]], provoked by the conscription of workers for the mines and deteriorating working conditions.<ref name=IS1/> That year the Belgians conducted a few \"police operations\" in the province of [[\u00c9quateur (former province)|\u00c9quateur]] to ensure disgruntled labourers would collect rubber.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} In 1945, riots and strikes occurred among the black dockworkers in the port city of [[Matadi]].<ref name=IS1>{{cite journal|title=Congo (Editorial)|journal=[[International Socialism (magazine)|International Socialism]]|date=Autumn 1960|volume=1|issue=2|url=https://www.marxists.org/history/etol/newspape/isj/1960/isj002/editorial4.htm}}</ref><ref name=Murindwa14/>\n\n===Luluabourg mutiny===\nThe colonial government in the Congo depended on its military to maintain civil order and, above all, it depended on the loyalty of the native troops who made up the bulk of the Force Publique. Black [[non-commissioned officers]] led by [[Belgian military ranks|First Sergeant-Major]] Ngoie Mukalabushi, a veteran of the East African Campaign,<ref name=Mwamba1/> mutinied at [[Kananga|Luluabourg]] in the central Congolese province of Kasa\u00ef in February 1944;<ref name=Mwamba1>{{cite book|last=Mwamba Mputu|first=Baudouin|title=Le Congo-Kasa\u00ef (1865\u20131950): De l'exploration allemande \u00e0 la cons\u00e9cration de Luluabourg|year=2011|publisher=L'Harmattan|location=Paris|chapter=IV: Mutinerie de Luluabourg de 1944}}<!--Note that there are no page numbers in the book so cannot be cited--></ref> the trigger for this was a plan to vaccinate troops who had served at the front, though the soldiers were also unhappy about the demands placed on them and their treatment by their white officers.<ref name=Mwamba1/>\n\nThe mutineers broke into the base's armoury on the morning of 20 February and pillaged the white quarter of the town.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The town's inhabitants fled, and a Belgian officer and two white civilians were killed.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The mutineers attacked visible signs of the colonial authorities and proclaimed their desire for independence.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The mutineers then dispersed to their home villages, pillaging on the way;<ref name=Mwamba1/> they failed to spread the insurrection to neighbouring garrisons.<ref name=Zeilig69/> Two mutineers, including Mukalabushi, were executed for their part in the insurrection.<ref name=Mwamba1/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| footer = Medals awarded for service in the Force Publique ''([[1940\u20131945 African War Medal|left]])'' and in the colonial war effort ''([[1940\u20131945 Colonial War Effort Medal|right]])''.\n| image1 = M\u00e9daille de la Guerre Africaine 1940-1945 Belgique.jpg\n| width1 = 76\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = M\u00e9daille de l'Effort de Guerre Colonial 1940-1945 Belgique.jpg\n| width2 = 74<!--please do not modify. with this width, the photo is same length as other at 76...-->\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 = \n}}\nOfficial postwar Belgian rhetoric portrayed the Congo's attitude towards the mother country as one of \"unfailing solidarity.\"{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=133}} As a result of the Congo's comparative prosperity during the conflict, the post-war period saw a wave of immigration to the country from Belgium. By 1950, 100,000 whites were living in the Congo.<ref name=Larousse1/> Nevertheless, the war highlighted the precarious nature of the colonial administration, leading Governor Ryckmans to remark that \"the days of colonialism are over\" in 1946.<ref name=Zeilig70/> A feeling by the Belgian government prevailed that it had incurred a \"war debt\" to the Congo, and thus more attention was given to the concerns of the indigenous population.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=77}} In the years after the war, the colonial government underwent extensive reform.<ref name=Zeilig70/> Black people were granted significantly more rights and freedoms, leading to the growth of a so-called ''[[\u00c9volu\u00e9]]'' (\"evolved\") class.<ref name=Zeilig71>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=71}}</ref> Despite this, the Belgian policy of conscripted labour of 60 days a year from each native Congolese remained in effect until Congolese independence, whereas similar labour levies were abolished in British and French possessions after the war.{{sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soriano|2018|p=293}} Several black members of the Force Publique who were veterans of the war served in prominent roles in the army after Congolese independence, including [[Louis Bobozo]], [[Eugene Ebeya]] and [[Norbert Muke]].<ref name= mobe>{{cite news| last = Mob\u00e9 Fansiama | first = Anicet| title = H\u00e9ros m\u00e9connus de la seconde guerre mondiale| newspaper = Le Monde diplomatique| pages = 34\u201335| language = French| date = June 2007| url = https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/2007/06/MOBE_FANSIAMA/14833| access-date = 13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the industrial unrest, trade unions for black workers were instituted in 1946, though they lacked power and influence.<ref name=Zeilig70>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=70}}</ref> Workers at the UMHK continued to demand higher wages, and strikes were common in the colony for the next decade.<ref name=Zeilig69/> Nevertheless, both wages and living conditions improved significantly in the years after the war.<ref name=Zeilig70/> The war began a second wave of industrialisation that lasted right up to Congolese independence in 1960.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buelens|first=Frans|author2=Cassimon, Danny|title=The Industrialization of the Belgian Congo|journal=\"Colonial Exploitation and Economic Development: The Belgian Congo and the Dutch East Indies Compared\" Conference|date=October 2011|url=http://vkc.library.uu.nl/vkc/seh/research/Lists/Events/Attachments/12/CH9.Buelens.Cassimon.IndustrializationCongo.pdf|location=University of Antwerp|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe 1941 \u00c9lisabethville massacre is a recurrent theme in Congolese art and folklore, and was later incorporated into the popular Congolese anti-colonial narrative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fabian|first=Johannes|authorlink=Johannes Fabian|title=Remembering the Present: Painting and Popular History in Zaire|year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=0-520-20376-3|pages=59\u201360|edition=2nd}}</ref> Historiographic discussion of the Congo's role in World War II is generally limited to mentions of the uranium extracted from Shinkolobwe.<ref>{{cite news| last = McCrummen| first = Stephanie| title = In Congo, men forced to fight in World War II are neglected, forgotten| newspaper = Boston Globe| page = A8| date = 9 August 2009}}</ref> The importance of Congolese uranium during the war caused the [[Soviet Union]] to become interested in the territory; it was subsequently an area of Soviet interest during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Borstelmann|first=Thomas|title=Apartheid, Colonialism, and the Cold War: the United States and Southern Africa, 1945\u20131952|year=1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=0-19-507942-6|pages=92\u201393}}</ref> The war also led to a re-orientation of the Congo's trade away from Belgium and towards the United States, the United Kingdom, and the United Kingdom's colonies.{{sfn|Martin|1985|pp=423\u2013424}}\n\n=== Commemoration ===\nIn 1943, a three-sided pyramid was erected in [[Faradje]], Belgian Congo to commemorate the actions of the Congolese in Ethiopia. Each face of the pyramid was inscribed with the name of each major location of fighting: Asosa, Gambela, and Sa\u00efo. Many locations throughout the country\u2014presently the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\u2014are named for the battles.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boneza |first=Ra\u00efs Neza |url=http://www.kimpavitapress.no/connecting-the-dot-congo-and-world-war-ii-one-of-the-other-forgotten-commemorations-by-ras-neza-boneza/ |access-date=10 March 2017 |title=Connecting the dot: Congo and World War II: One of the Other Forgotten Commemorations |publisher=Kimpavita Press & Publishers |location=Trondheim |date=7 June 2014}}</ref> In 1970 the Belgian government dedicated a monument in [[Schaerbeek]], Belgium, to the military successes of Belgian colonial forces, including those during World War II.{{sfn|Stanard|2009|p=112}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Democratic Republic of the Congo|World War II}}\n*[[Belgium in World War II]]\n*[[Free Belgian Forces]]\n*[[Ruzagayura famine]] (1943\u201344)\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Works cited ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Byfield|first1=Judith A.|last2=Brown|first2=Carolyn A.|last3=Parsons|first3=Timothy|last4=Sikainga|first4=Ahmad Alawad|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=tjoPCAAAQBAJ&dq=|title=Africa and World War II|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107053205|ref = {{harvid|Byfield et al.|2015}}}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Martin| first = Phyllis M.| title = Reviewed Work: Le Congo Belge durant la Seconde Guerre Mondiale: Recueil d'Etudes.| journal = The Journal of African History| volume = 26| issue = 4| pages = 422\u2013424| date = 1985| jstor = 181666| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Farrell-Robert| first = Janine| title = Glitter & Greed: The Secret World of the Diamond Cartel| publisher = Red Wheel Weiser| edition = revised| date = 2007| location =| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bHxgFQssc2IC| isbn = 9781609258801| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Fern\u00e1ndez Soriano| first = Victor| title = \u2018Travail et progr\u00e8s\u2019: Obligatory \u2018Educational\u2019 Labour in the Belgian Congo, 1933\u201360| journal = Journal of Contemporary History| volume = 53| issue = 2| pages = 292\u2013314| date = 2018| doi = 10.1177/0022009417697807| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Geenen| first = Kristien| title = Categorizing colonial patients: Segregated medical care, space and decolonization in a Congolese city, 1931\u201362| journal = The Journal of the International African Institute| volume = 89| issue = 1| pages = 100\u2013124| date = 2019| issn = 1750-0184| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch. Didier| title = The History of Congo | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| series = Greenwood histories of the modern nations| ISSN = 1096-2905| edition = illustrated, annotated| date = 2002| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780313316968| url-access = registration | isbn = 978-0-313-31696-8|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Pepin| first = Jacques| title = The Origins of AIDS| publisher = Cambridge University Press| date = 2011| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dTaMBrPBK6EC| isbn = 9781139501415| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stanard| first = Matthew| title = The Leopard, the Lion, and the Cock: Colonial Memories and Monuments in Belgium| publisher = Leuven University Press| date = 2009| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K4uRDwAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9789462701793| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Stanard| first = Matthew G.| title = Belgium, the Congo, and Imperial Immobility: A Singular Empire and the Historiography of the Single Analytic Field| journal = French Colonial History| volume = 15| pages = 87\u2013109| date = 2014| url = http://muse.jhu.edu/article/547759| issn = 1543-7787| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Van der Wee| first = Herman| last2 = Verbreyt| first2 = Monique| title = A Small Nation in the Turmoil of the Second World War: Money, Finance and Occupation (Belgium, Its Enemies, Its Friends, 1939-1945)| publisher = Leuven University Press| edition = revised| date = 2009| location = Leuven| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ptEjPQjtNGwC| isbn = 9789058677594| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Vanthemsche|first=Guy|title=Belgium and the Congo, 1885\u20131980|date=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-19421-1|ref={{harvid|Vanthemsche|2012}}}}\n* {{cite book| last = Veranneman| first = Jean-Michel| title = Belgium in the Second World War| publisher = Pen and Sword| edition = illustrated| date = 2014| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MmVtBQAAQBAJ&dq=|location=Barnsley| isbn = 9781783376070|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Weller|1942}}\n|last=Weller |first=George |author-link=George Weller |title=The Belgian Campaign in Ethiopia: A Trek of 2,500 Miles through Jungle Swamps and Desert Wastes |year=1942 |publisher=Belgian Information Center |location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Ethiopia/index.html|oclc=1452395}}\n* {{cite book| last = Willame| first = Jean-Claude| title = Patrimonialism and Political Change in the Congo| publisher = Stanford University Press| location = Stanford | date = 1972| ref = harv| url = https://archive.org/details/patrimonialismpo0000will| url-access = registration| isbn = 978-0-8047-0793-0}}\n* {{cite book| last = Williams| first = Susan| title = Spies in the Congo: The Race for the Ore that Built the Atomic Bomb| publisher = Oxford University Press| date = 2018| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nzjXCwAAQBAJ| isbn = 9781787380653| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Young| first = Crawford| title = Politics in the Congo: Decolonization and Independence|location= Princeton| publisher = Princeton University Press| date = 1965| ref = harv| oclc= 307971}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category|Belgian Congo in World War II}}\n;Primary sources\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=de Vleeschauwer|first=Albert|authorlink=Albert de Vleeschauwer|title=Belgian Colonial Policy|year=1943|publisher=Belgian Information Center|location=New York|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b583254;view=1up;seq=1}}\n{{refend}}\n;Thematic studies\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Peeters|first=Natasja|title=Lisolo na Bisu, 1885\u20131960: \"Our History\" the Congolese Soldier of the \"Force Publique\"|year=2010|publisher=[[Royal Museum of the Armed Forces and of Military History|KLM-MRA]]|location=Brussels|isbn=2-87051-049-7}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Lovens|first=Maurice|title=L'effort militaire de guerre du Congo belge (1940\u20131944)|journal=Les cahiers du CEDAF|year=1975|volume=|issue=6|pages=1\u201334|language=fr}} \n*{{cite journal|last=Ermens|first=Paul|title=L'effort de guerre de la Force Publique du Congo belge|journal=[[Za\u00efre. Revue Congolaise-Congoleesch Tijdschrift]]|date=January 1947|volume=1 | issue = 1|pages=7\u201334|language=fr}}\n*{{cite book|last=Brousmiche|first=Philippe|title=Borta\u00ef: Campagne d'Abyssinie|year=2011|publisher=L'Harmattan|location=Paris|isbn=978-2-296-13069-2|language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Vanderwalle|first=F.A.|title=Mutineries au Congo Belge|journal=Za\u00efre: Revue Congolaise-Congoleesch Tijdschrift|date=May 1947|volume=1 | issue = 2|pages=485\u2013514|language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Van Maele|first=Beno\u00eet|title=De buitenlandse betrekkingen an Belgisch Congo aan de vooravond van de Tweede Wereldoorlog (1939\u20131940)|journal=Thesis (University of Ghent)|year=1999|url=http://www.ethesis.net/congo_1939_1940/congo_1939_1940_inhoud.htm|language=nl}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Buch|first1=Pierre|first2=Jacques|last2=Vanderlinden|title=L'uranium, la Belgique et les puissances: march\u00e9 de dupes ou chef d'\u0153uvre diplomatique?|publisher =De Boeck| location=Brussels|year=1995|isbn=978-2-8041-1993-5|language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Banjikila|first=Bakajika|title=Les Ouvriers du Haut-Katanga Pendant la Deuxi\u00e8me Guerre Mondiale|journal=Revue d'histoire de la Deuxi\u00e8me Guerre mondiale et des conflits contemporains|date=April 1983|volume=33|issue=130|pages=91\u2013108|jstor=25729091|language=fr}} \n{{refend}}\n\n{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2013}}\n\n{{Democratic Republic of the Congo topics}}\n{{WWII history by nation}}\n\n[[Category:Belgian Congo in World War II| ]]\n[[Category:1940s in the Belgian Congo|World War II]]\n[[Category:Belgium in World War II|Congo]]\n[[Category:History of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|World War II]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|World War II]]\n[[Category:1940s in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Belgian Congo Leopoldville square.jpg|thumb|A busy city square in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], capital of the Belgian Congo, 1943|275px]]\n\nThe involvement of the [[Belgian Congo]] (the modern-day [[Democratic Republic of Congo]]) in [[World War II]] began with the German invasion of Belgium in May 1940. Despite Belgium's surrender, the Congo remained in the conflict on the [[Allies (World War II)|Allied side]], administered by the [[Belgian government in exile]], and provided much-needed raw materials, most notably [[uranium]], to the United Kingdom and the United States.\n\nCongolese troops of the [[Force Publique]] fought alongside British forces in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]], and a Congolese medical unit served in [[Battle of Madagascar|Madagascar]] and in the [[Burma Campaign]]. Congolese formations also acted as garrisons in [[Kingdom of Egypt|Egypt]], [[Colony and Protectorate of Nigeria|Nigeria]] and [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]].\n\nThe increasing demands placed on the Congolese population by the colonial authorities during the war, however, provoked strikes, riots and other forms of resistance, particularly from the indigenous Congolese. These were repressed, often violently, by the Belgian colonial authorities. The Congo's comparative prosperity during the conflict led to a wave of post-war immigration from Belgium, bringing the white population to 100,000 by 1950, as well as a period of industrialisation that continued throughout the 1950s. The role played by Congolese uranium during the hostilities caused the country to be of interest to the [[Soviet Union]] during the [[Cold War]].\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Battle of Belgium|German occupation of Belgium during World War II}}\n[[File:Monument Albert Kinshasa 5.JPG|thumb|Colonial officials, including the Governor-General, [[Pierre Ryckmans (Governor-General)|Pierre Ryckmans]], in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] in 1938.]]\n\nFollowing World War I, Belgium possessed two colonies in Africa: the [[Belgian Congo]], which it had controlled since its annexation of the [[Congo Free State]] in 1908, and [[Ruanda-Urundi]], a former German colony that had been mandated to Belgium in 1924 by the [[League of Nations]].<ref name=Larousse1>{{cite web|title=Empire Colonial Belge|url=http://www.larousse.fr/encyclopedie/autre-region/Empire_colonial_belge/182725|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions Larousse]]|work=Online Encyclopedia|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> The Belgian colonial military numbered 18,000 soldiers, making it one of the largest standing colonial armies in Africa at the time.<ref name=Killingray7>{{cite book|last=Killingray|first=David|title=Fighting for Britain: African soldiers in the Second World War|year=2010|publisher=James Currey|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-84701-015-5|page=7}}</ref> The Congo underwent an economic boom in the 1920s and mines, plantations, and transportation networks were greatly developed. The [[Great Depression]] led to a collapse of commodity prices, undermining the colony's export-based economy and leading to a large reduction in income and employment. The only industry that expanded during the time period was centered around [[cotton]] production.<ref>{{cite journal| last = G\u00e9rard-Libois| first = Jules| last2 = Verhaegen| first2 = Beno\u00eet| title = Le Congo: Du domaine de L\u00e9opold II \u00e0 l\u2019ind\u00e9pendance| journal =  Courrier hebdomadaire du CRISP| issue = 1077| pages = 1\u201334| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| date = 26 April 1985| language = French| url = https://www.cairn.info/revue-courrier-hebdomadaire-du-crisp-1985-12-page-1.htm| doi = 10.3917/cris.1077.0001}}</ref>\n\nThe Belgian government followed a policy of neutrality during the interwar years. [[Nazi Germany]] invaded Belgium on 10 May 1940 which, after [[Battle of Belgium|18 days of fighting]], surrendered and was [[German occupation of Belgium during World War II|occupied]] by German forces. [[Leopold III of Belgium|King Leopold III]], who had surrendered to the Germans, was kept a prisoner for the rest of the war.<ref name=Yapou1>{{cite book|last=Yapou|first=Eliezer|title=Governments in Exile, 1939\u20131945|year=1998|location=Jerusalem|url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapoubelgium.html|chapter=4: Belgium: Disintegration and Resurrection}}</ref> Just before the fall of Belgium, its government, including the Minister of the Colonies, [[Albert de Vleeschauwer]], fled to [[Bordeaux]] in France.<ref name=Yapou1/>\n\n== Entry of the Congo into the war ==\nOn 10 May 1940 Belgian officials formally requested that the United Kingdom and France declare their respect for the Congo's neutrality and support for its territorial integrity in a future peace settlement. The British government refused, wanting to ensure that the Congo would not fall under German control, and France followed suit. The French government briefly considered sending troops to occupy [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], the Congolese capital.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=122}} On the day of the Belgian Army's surrender, the British government, uncertain about what would happen to the territory, held a crisis meeting in London. The [[Admiralty]] proposed sending troops to occupy strategic locations in the Congo, but this was quickly ruled unfeasible due to other military commitments. The British government then resolved that if the Belgian government collapsed, it would support an \"independent\" Congo.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=125\u2013126}}\n\nWithin the Congo itself, opinion was divided on whether or not to continue to support the war. Belgian corporate officials hoped that the colony would take a neutral stance, and the staff of the [[Force Publique]], the colonial army, recommended a declaration of neutrality or even independence under the authority of the [[List of colonial governors of the Congo Free State and Belgian Congo|Governor-General of the Congo]], [[Pierre Ryckmans (Governor-General)|Pierre Ryckmans]]. Ryckmans refused to take this advice,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=127}} and declared on the day of the Belgian Army's surrender that the colony would remain loyal to the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]].<ref name=Urome>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=L'Histoire du Congo vue par les Coloniaux|publisher=Urome.be|url=http://www.urome.be/pdf/fhisconbe.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref> Despite this assurance, disruption broke out in the city of [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]] (now Kisangani in the eastern Congo) among the white population panicking about the future of the colony and the threat of an Italian invasion.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nOn 17 June France declared an armistice with Germany. Though Ryckmans had declared that he would continue to support the Allied cause, the Belgian government in Bordeaux was deeply disheartened by the French surrender.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=72, 231}} Prime Minister [[Hubert Pierlot]] believed that it lacked the resources to continue to fight and thus it would be better to negotiate a peace with Germany instead of going into exile in the United Kingdom. Most of the ministers agreed, though de Vleeschauwer dissented. While the government prepared to negotiate with Germany, representatives of various Belgo-Congolese companies in Bordeaux informed the ministers of rumours that should Belgium surrender, the United Kingdom would seize control of the Congo.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=72\u201373}} Meanwhile, some circles in occupied Belgium feared that if the Congo aligned itself with the Allies it would be permanently lost as a colony to Belgium. In Brussels, the Germans established a \"Kolonial Politisches B\u00fcro\" that attempted to forge connections with what remained of the Ministry of Colonies.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=124\u2013125}}\n\nThe British were determined that the Congo should not fall into Axis hands, and planned to invade and occupy the colony if the Belgians did not come to an arrangement. This was particularly because the Allies were desperate for raw materials like [[natural rubber|rubber]] which the Congo could produce in abundance.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} On 20 June the British Foreign Secretary told the Belgian ambassador in London that the United Kingdom would not accept German dominance over the colony.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=231}} Meanwhile, the Belgo-Congolese businessmen proposed that de Vleeschauwer go to London to ensure that Belgian sovereignty over the Congo would be respected. Pierlot suggested that de Vleeschauwer should be granted the new title of Administrator-general of the Congo, allowing him to pursue this cause even if the government later collapsed and his ministerial mandate became void.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=73\u201374, 232}}  The government agreed to the idea, and on 18 June it passed a law-decree, granting de Vleeschauwer the title and conferring on him full legislative and executive power to manage the Congo. The decree also stipulated that in the event the administrator-general was unable to exercise his duties, the responsibility would be passed on to the governor-general.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=123, 132}}\n\nDe Vleeschauwer departed for London, arriving on 4 July.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=73\u201374, 232}} He spoke with members of the British government and assured them that he would place all of the Congo's raw materials at the disposal of the United Kingdom's war effort. Over the following months Pierlot and two other ministers managed to reach London while the rest declared their intention to remain in France and resign. In October Pierlot, de Vleeschauwer, and the two other ministers officially established the [[Belgian government in exile]], recognised by the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=232\u2013233}} Despite his presence, de Vleeschauwer was politically marginalised by Finance Minister [[Camille Gutt]] and played little role thereafter in the government.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=237\u2013238}} There was also conflict between de Vleeschauwer, who wanted to assure his own authority over the Congo, and Foreign Minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] who sought to be more conciliatory with regard to Allied influence in the colony.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=131}}\n\nThe Germans were upset by the Congo's support for the Allies, and threatened to apply sanctions to Belgian colonial enterprises. Leopold III expressed his discontent with Ryckman's decisions, believing that the colony should remain neutral.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=128}} Royalist politicians sent messages to the Belgian authorities in London, attempting to dissuade them from allowing the Congo support the British war effort. In October 1940 Leopold III requested permission from Nazi German leader [[Adolf Hitler]] to dispatch an emissary to L\u00e9opoldville to persuade the colonial administration to assume neutrality, but the trip was never authorised.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=128\u2013129}}\n\n==Economic contribution==\n=== Allied support ===\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote=\"The Belgian Congo has entered the service of the Allies. Its economic doctrine and practices have been rapidly adapted to the new conditions and, whilst everything is being done to maintain the potentiality of the Congo wealth, there is no hesitation whatsoever when it comes to sacrificing any riches in favor of the war effort.\"|2=[[Albert de Vleeschauwer]], Minister of the Colonies, 1942<ref name=TBCAW1>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=3|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Pilot Officer H. A. Picard of No. 350 (Belgian) Squadron, on the wing of his Spitfire at Kenley, July 1942. CH6356.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A Belgian pilot in the British [[Royal Air Force]], 1942. His [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] aircraft was funded by contributions from the Congo, and took its name, \"Luvungi\", from [[Luvungi|the Congolese town]] of that name.]]\nSoon after the establishment of the Belgian government in exile in London, negotiations began between the Belgians and the British about the role which the Congo would play in the Allied war effort.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} The two parties came to an arrangement on 21 January 1941, in which all the British demands were accepted, including a 30 percent [[devaluation]] of the [[Congolese franc]] and the entrance of the Congo into the [[sterling area]].{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}}{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=235}} With the official agreement and the Congolese declaration of support for the Allies, the economy of the Congo\u2014in particular its production of important raw materials\u2014was placed at the disposal of the Allies.<ref name=TBCAW1/> Though Ryckmans and leaders of the [[Banque du Congo Belge]] (the Congo's [[central bank]]) were pleased at the entry into the sterling area, which guaranteed an export market for the territory, they strongly disliked the fixed prices the agreement entailed which were favourable to the United Kingdom and worried that only trading with sterling could negatively impact the Congo's [[foreign exchange reserves]]. Business leaders in the colony were disgruntled as well, and boosted production of goods not mentioned in the agreement to sell to the neutral United States at their standard market value.{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|p=235}} In 1942, after the United States joined the Allies, the Belgian government negotiated a new economic agreement with the United States and United Kingdom. Belgian officials never signed it, but it was ''de facto'' applied for the rest of the war,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=130}} and Congolese trade remained directed at the two countries.<ref name=TBCAW1/> The Congo's economic output became an even more valuable asset to the Allies after Japan occupied large swathes of South East Asia in 1942, halting those areas' exports of key tropical commodities such as rubber.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}}\n\n[[File:Sheets of copper from Katanga mines, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Sheets of copper from the [[Katanga Province]]'s mines]]\n\nThe Congo had become increasingly centralised economically during the Great Depression of the 1930s, as the Belgian government encouraged the production there of cotton, which had value on the international market.<ref name=Larousse1/> The greatest economic demands on the Congo during the war were related to raw materials. Between 1938 and 1944, the number of workers employed in the mines of the ''[[Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga]]'' (UMHK) rose from 25,000 to 49,000 to cope with the increased demand.<ref name=Zeilig66>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=66}}</ref> The colonial administration enacted ultimately successful policies aimed at increasing the size of the Congo's labour force; the number of wage labourers in the colony grew from 480,000 in 1938 to 800,000 in 1945.{{sfn|Martin|1985|p=423}} In order to increase production for the war effort, the colonial authorities increased the hours and the speed at which workers, both European and African, were expected to work. This led to increasing [[labour unrest]] across the colony.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} [[Forced labour]], which had been banned in the 1930s, was reintroduced to keep up with demand; by 1944, the maximum number of days of forced labour per year was raised to 120 for rural Congolese.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=99}} Discontent among the white population was also increased by the raising of heavy war taxes, which sometimes reached as high as 40 percent.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=81}} High taxes and price controls were enforced from 1941, limiting the amount of profit that could be made and curbing [[War profiteering|profiteering]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=8|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> While the price controls aided exports to the Allies, it adversely affected Congolese peasants, who earned less despite their increased amount of labour.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=99}}\n\nThe vast majority of the Congolese-produced raw resources were exported to other Allied countries. According to the Belgian government, by 1942 the entire colony's output of [[copper]] and [[palm oil]] were being exported to the United Kingdom, while almost all the colony's lumber was sent to South Africa.<ref name=BCAW11>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=11|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> Exports to the United States also rose from [[United States Dollar|$]]600,000 in early 1940 to $2,700,000 by 1942.<ref name=BCAW12>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=12|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> Despite the Allied cooperation, many officials of the colonial administration treated American and British diplomats with suspicion, fearing the potential economic rivalry posed by their countries to Belgian enterprises.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}\n\nAs per a deal reached on 21 March 1941, loans from the Banque du Congo Belge enabled the Belgian government in exile and [[Free Belgian Forces]] to fund themselves, unlike most other states in exile, which operated through subsidies and donations from sympathetic governments.<ref name=Zeilig66/>{{sfn|Van der Wee|Verbreyt|2009|pp=236\u2013237}} It also meant that the Belgian gold reserves, which had been moved to London in 1940, were not needed to fund the war effort, and therefore were still available at the end of the war.<ref name=Zeilig66/>\n\n===Uranium===\n[[Uranium-235]] was mined in the Congo at [[Shinkolobwe]] in [[Katanga Province|Katanga]] before the war by the UMHK for export to Belgium. It was originally used by the medical industry, for radium production, and for coloring ceramics. Scientists in Europe later discovered that enriched uranium could be used in the production of a supposed [[atomic bomb]]. When physicist [[Albert Einstein]] wrote U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt to warn him of the possibility of a German atomic bomb program, he advised him that the Congo was a main source of the mineral.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=83}} Uranium extracted from the disused Shinkolobwe mine ultimately proved instrumental in the development of an atomic bomb during the Allied [[Manhattan Project]]. The director of UMHK, [[Edgar Sengier]], secretly dispatched half of its uranium stock to [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1940; in September 1942, he sold it to the [[United States Army]].<ref>{{cite news |first=William J. |last=Broad |authorlink= |title=Why They Called It the Manhattan Project |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/30/science/30manh.html|work=[[New York Times]] |date=30 October 2007 |accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nSengier himself moved to [[New York (state)|New York]], from where he directed the UMHK's operations for the rest of the war.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael|last=Pollack |authorlink= |title=Answers to Questions About New York City|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/27/nyregion/27fyi.html |work=[[New York Times]]|date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref> The U.S. government sent soldiers from the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] to Shinkolobwe in 1942 to restore the mine and improve its transport links by renovating the local aerodromes and port facilities.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hunt|first=Margaret R.|title=Manhattan-Uranium Connection sidenotes|url=http://www3.amherst.edu/~mrhunt/uranium/notes8.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060918220848/http://www.amherst.edu/~mrhunt/uranium/notes8.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 September 2006|publisher=Amherst College|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> In September 1944 the Belgian government reached an agreement with the United Kingdom and the United States, whereby it would sell only those two countries the Congolese uranium at a fixed price.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=134}} That year the Americans acquired a further {{convert|1720|LT}} of Uranium ore from the newly reopened mine.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Oscar E.|last2=Hewlett|first2=Richard G.|authorlink2=Richard G. Hewlett|title=The New World, 1939\u20131946|year=1990|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, Calif.|url=https://www.governmentattic.org/5docs/TheNewWorld1939-1946.pdf|format=PDF|isbn=0-520-07186-7|edition=Reprint|pages=285\u2013288}}</ref>\n\n=== German diamond trafficking ===\nDuring the war there were frequent rumors that some Belgian industrialists involved in colonial enterprises were covertly aiding Germany.{{sfn|Williams|2018|pp=49\u201350}} American officials found working with Belgo-Congolese mining companies to secure [[industrial diamonds]] to be difficult.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}} According to the Belgian government, by 1942 the entire colony's output of industrial diamonds was being shipped to the United Kingdom.<ref name=BCAW11/> In reality, many industrial diamonds were smuggled to Nazi Germany for use in the German war effort. Most Congolese diamonds were mined by [[Formini\u00e8re]], a subsidiary of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Belgique]], which was in turn a member of the [[De Beers]] Diamond Syndicate. In 1940, the Syndicate reported that the Congo annually produced 10.9 million carats of diamonds. Immediately after the outbreak of war reported production sharply declined, and by 1942 production had officially fallen to 5 million carats\u2013roughly the original production number minus the amount exported to Germany before the war. Believing that a large volume of diamonds were being smuggled out of the colony, American intelligence officials convinced British agents to inspect the security of the mines. The officer tasked with overseeing the inspection teams concluded that proper security measures were lacking and that Formini\u00e8re and [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 mini\u00e8re de Beceka]] personnel fostered a \"sinister atmosphere\" during the tours.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}} Firmin van Bree, the director of Formini\u00e8re, was widely suspected of maintaining German sympathies.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}{{sfn|Williams|2018|p=50}} The German government conducted secret negotiations with leaders of Formini\u00e8re and the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale, and reached deals that allowed them to purchase large quantities of diamonds until 1944. In 1943 Germany paid the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale $10.5 million for diamonds. American and British agents ultimately uncovered a wide smuggling network that brought diamonds out of the Congo and to German-occupied Europe by air and sea. Proposals by the Americans to stifle the illicit trade were dissuaded by the British [[Ministry of Economic Warfare]], whose Diamond Committee was dominated by members of the De Beers Diamond Syndicate. After the end of the war the Belgian government demanded that Germany pay $25 million owed to the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale for 576,676 carats of diamonds.{{sfn|Farrell-Robert|2007|loc=Chapter 7 - Diamonds for Hitler}}\n\n==Military involvement==\n=== Force Publique ===\n[[File:Belgian Congo enlisting for the Force Publique.jpg|thumb|275px|Congolese enlisting in the Force Publique following the outbreak of war]]\nThe [[Force Publique]] (or \"Public Force\") was the combined police and military force of both the Congo and Ruanda-Urundi. During World War II, it constituted the bulk of the [[Free Belgian Forces]],<ref name=Killingray7/> numbering over 40,000 men at its peak in 1943.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=98}} Like other colonial armies of the time, the Force Publique was racially segregated;{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=62}} it was led by 280 white officers and NCOs, but otherwise comprised indigenous black Africans.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buzin|first=Jean|title=The \"Belgian Congo Air Force.\" The Air Force that Never Was&nbsp;... |journal=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Royale des Pionniers et Anciens de l'Aviation Belge|url=http://www.vieillestiges.be/files/articles/belgiancongoairforce_fr.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> The Force Publique had never received the more modern equipment supplied to the [[Belgian Armed Forces]] before the war, and so had to use outdated weapons and equipment like the [[Stokes mortar]] and the [[70 mm St Chamond mountain howitzer|Saint Chamond 70&nbsp;mm howitzer]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bellis|first=Malcolm A.|title=Commonwealth Divisions: 1939\u20131945|year=1999|publisher=Selbstverl.|location=Crewe|isbn=0-9529693-0-0|edition=1st|page=45}}</ref> During the war the force was expanded through recruitment and the calling up of reserves.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=98}}\n\n===East African Campaign===\n{{main|East African Campaign (World War II)}}\n\nWhile willing to mobilise the Congo's economic resources for the Allied war effort, the Belgian government in exile was initially much more hesitant to deploy Congolese troops in combat. The government also refused to declare war on Germany's ally, Italy, which had colonies in Africa and was fighting to secure British possessions in the continent,{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|pp=126, 128\u2013129}} because the Belgian royal family had dynastic links with the Italian royal family. This attitude changed after it became known that Italian aircraft based in occupied Belgium were attacking Britain and when an Italian submarine sank a Belgian cargo ship. A Belgian declaration of war was eventually delivered against Italy on 23 November 1940.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=84}} Two days later, Ryckmans proclaimed that a state of war existed between Italy and the Congo.{{sfn|Weller|1942|p=5}}\n\n[[File:Force Publique leaving for Ethiopia.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Force Publique]] soldiers leaving the Congo to participate in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]] in Ethiopia|left]]\nThree brigades of the Force Publique were sent to [[Italian East Africa]] alongside British forces to fight the Italians.<ref name=Yapou1/> The Belgian 1st Colonial Brigade operated in the Galla-Sidamo area in the South-West sector.<ref name=\"Ready 1985 45\">{{cite book|last=Ready|first=J. Lee|title=Forgotten Allies: the Military Contribution of the Colonies, Exiled Governments, and Lesser Powers to the Allied Victory in World War II|year=1985|publisher=Mcfarland|location=Jefferson|volume=I|isbn=0-7864-7168-9|page=45}}</ref> In May 1941, around 8,000 men of the Force Publique, under Major-General [[Auguste-\u00c9douard Gilliaert]], successfully [[Siege of Sa\u00efo|cut off]] the retreat of General [[Pietro Gazzera]]'s Italians at [[Dembidolo|Sa\u00efo]], in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] after marching over {{convert|1,000|km}} from their bases in western Congo. The troops suffered from [[malaria]] and other tropical diseases, but successfully defeated the Italians in a number of engagements.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}} Gilliaert subsequently accepted the surrender of Gazzera and 7,000 Italian troops.<ref name=\"Ready 1985 45\"/> Over the course of the campaign in Ethiopia, the Force Publique received the surrender of nine Italian generals, 370 high-ranking officers and 15,000 Italian colonial troops before the end of 1941.{{sfn|Weller|1942|p=3}} The Congolese forces in Ethiopia suffered about 500 fatalities.<ref name=Killingray7/>\n\nAfter the Allied victory in Ethiopia, the Force Publique moved to the British colony of Nigeria, which was being used as a staging ground for a planned invasion of [[French Dahomey|Vichy-controlled Dahomey]] which did not occur,{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|pp=84\u201385}} was also garrisoned by 13,000 Congolese troops.<ref name=Killingray7/> Then a part of the Force Publique went to [[Kingdom of Egypt|Egypt]] and British [[Mandatory Palestine]] and was redesignated the 1st Belgian Congo Brigade Group during 1943 and 1944.<ref name=Thomas17>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|title=Foreign Volunteers of the Allied Forces, 1939\u201345|year=1991|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-85532-136-6|page=17}}</ref>\n\n===Medical support===\nA medical unit from the Congo, the 10th (Belgian Congo) [[Casualty Clearing Station]], was formed in 1943, and served alongside British forces during the [[Battle of Madagascar|invasion of Madagascar]] and in the Far East during the [[Burma Campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Epilogue Oriental|url=http://www.mil.be/vox/subject/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=612&MENU=916&PAGE=2|accessdate=2 July 2013|newspaper=VOX|date=16 June 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209023739/http://www.mil.be/vox/subject/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=612&MENU=916&PAGE=2|archivedate=9 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The unit (which had a small body of Force Publique troops for local defense of the station) included 350 black and 20 white personnel, and continued to serve with the British until 1945.<ref>{{cite web|title=Burma: The 10th Belgian Congo Casualty Clearing Station, 1945|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205058818|publisher=[[Imperial War Museum]]|accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life in the Belgian Congo==\n[[File:Belgian Congo houses built for Congolese workers.jpg|thumb|Congolese worker housing, c. 1943]]\nAt the start of the war, the population of the Congo numbered approximately 12&nbsp;million black people and 30,000 whites.<ref>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=65|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> The colonial government segregated the population along racial lines and there was very little mixing between the colours.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lagae|first=Johan|title=Rewriting Congo's Colonial Past: History, Memory, and Colonial Built Heritage in Lubumbashi, Democratic Republic of the Congo|year=2005|publisher=Institut national d'histoire et d'art|location=Paris|url=http://inha.revues.org/499#text|chapter=The built fabric of a segregated city}}</ref> The white population was highly urbanized and, in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], lived in [[Gombe, Kinshasa|a quarter]] of the city separated from the black majority. All blacks in the city had to adhere to a [[curfew]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Njoh|first=Ambe J.|title=Planning Power: Social Control and Planning in Colonial Africa|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=1-84472-160-4|page=217}}</ref> The colonial authorities arrested [[enemy alien]]s in the Congo and confiscated their property in 1940.<ref name=bic7>{{cite book|last=Various authors|first=|title=The Belgian Congo at War|year=1942|publisher=Belgian Information Center|page=7|location=New York|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Belgium/Congo/}}</ref> The colonial administration tried to conceal the war from the African population by censoring the media, but the Congolese noticed the internal tensions among the white population and the detention of German and Italian nationals.{{sfn|Geenen|2019|p=114}} To better counter external influences in the colony, the administration established a Bureau of Information and Propaganda.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=102}}\n\nThe demands of the colonial administration fell hardest on rural residents, which were conscripted for road construction projects and rubber harvesting. Conditions were harsh for the labourers, and in some cases were conflated in the Congolese [[collective memory]] with the earlier atrocities committed by the Congo Free State in relation to [[Atrocities in the Congo Free State#Red Rubber system and forced labour|its rubber collection system]].{{sfn|Martin|1985|p=423}} The urbanised Congolese generally experienced more financial gain during the war than their rural counterparts, though several workers who had collected large amounts of rubber earned even more money.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} During the war the Belgian government in exile directed propaganda at the Allied states that created a positive image of its colony in an attempt to legitimise its rule. In [[New York City]], the Belgian Information Center released numerous publications which asserted that the Belgians had rescued the Congolese from \"terrible conditions\" and improved life in the territory.{{sfn|Stanard|2014|p=98}} Wider Allied propaganda also downplayed internal political tensions within the Congo and in its relations with the Belgian government so as to portray the coordination of its war effort in a harmonious fashion.{{sfn|Vanthemsche|2012|p=130}}\n\nEducation was overwhelmingly controlled by Protestant and Catholic missions, which were also responsible for providing limited welfare support to the rural Congolese.<ref name=BCAW11/> The occupation of Belgium severed Belgian missionaries from their parent organisations, causing the colonial administration to subsidise their activities to make up for budget deficits. The war did not adversely impact their evangelising, and the number of reported baptisms conducted increased from 1,824,000 in 1939 to a cumulative total of 2,214,000 in 1942.<ref>{{cite news| title = Activity of the Social Services in the Belgian Congo in the War| newspaper = News From Belgium| volume = IV| issue = 22| date = 3 June 1944| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERbPAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> Healthcare was provided by a mix of government and corporate physicians, private practitioners, and missionaries. At the outbreak of the war there were 302 doctors working in the Congo. Some medical personnel accompanied the Force Publique on its foreign deployments, but the vast majority remained in the colony for the conflict's duration. Unlike the neighboring French possessions, the war did not adversely affect the resources of healthcare providers in the Congo. Medical research continued and a new journal was created so that findings could be published while the territory was separated from Belgium.{{sfn|Pepin|2011|p=145}}\n\nFood remained unrationed during the war, with only the sales of tires and automobiles restricted by the government.<ref name=BCAW11/> Nevertheless, the war did lead to a shortage of consumer goods.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} The devaluation of the Congolese franc also made foreign imports more expensive.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} One of the consequences of the Congo's economic mobilisation during the war, particularly for the black population, was significant [[urbanisation]]. Just 9% of the indigenous population lived in cities in 1938; by 1950, the figure stood at close to 20%.<ref name=IS1/> The colonial government also greatly improved transport and production facilities during the war.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}}\n\n==Unrest==\n\n===Strikes===\n[[File:Katanga mine worker, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Katangese miner]]\nThe demands made by the colonial government on Congolese workers during the war provoked strikes and riots from the workforce. Whites in the colony were allowed to form [[trade union]]s for the first time during the war, and their demands for better pay and working conditions were often emulated by black workers.<ref name= higginson/> A lack of European skilled labor forced the colonial government to train and give native Congolese skilled labor positions for the first time, but they were paid less than their white colleagues, generating discontent.{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=82}} In October 1941, white workers in the colony unsuccessfully attempted a [[general strike]] across the colony.<ref name= higginson>{{cite book|last=Higginson|first=John|title=A Working Class in the Making: Belgian Colonial Labor Policy, Private Enterprise, and the African Mineworker, 1907\u20131951|year=1989|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wis.|isbn=0-299-12070-8|page=188|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote=\"Why should a white man be paid more than a black, when all the white man does is stand there, giving orders, his arms behind his back and with his pipe in his mouth? We should take our rights, or we won't work tomorrow.\"|2=L\u00e9onard Mpoyi, December 1941<ref name=Zeilig68/>}}\nIn December 1941, black mine workers at various sites in [[Katanga Province]], including [[Likasi|Jadotville]] and [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], went on strike, demanding that their pay be increased from 1.50 [[Congolese franc|francs]] to 2 francs to compensate for rising living costs.<ref name=Murindwa14>{{cite book|last=Rutanga|first=Murindwa|title=Politics, Religion and Power in the Great Lakes Region|year=2011|publisher=Council for the Development of Social Science Research in Africa (CODESRIA)|location=Dakar|isbn=2-86978-492-9|page=14}}</ref><ref name=BBC1>{{cite web|title=The Story of Africa: World War II|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1624_story_of_africa/page20.shtml|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 July 2013}}</ref> The strike started on 3 December, and by the next day 1,400 workers had downed tools.<ref>{{cite book|last=Higginson|first=John|title=A Working Class in the Making: Belgian Colonial Labor Policy, Private Enterprise, and the African Mineworker, 1907\u20131951|year=1989|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wis.|isbn=0-299-12070-8|page=189|edition=1st}}</ref> All UMHK sites were affected by 9 December.<ref name=Zeilig68>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=68}}</ref> The strike was also fueled by other grievances against the colonial order and segregation.{{citation needed|date= April 2020}} \n\n[[File:Elizabethville Massacre (Matulu).jpg|thumb|A painting of the \u00c9lisabethville massacre by [[Tshibumba Kanda-Matulu]], a Congolese artist, depicting the church and colonial state (personified at the right) as the instigators]]\nFrom the start, the colonial authorities attempted to persuade the strikers to disperse and go back to work. When they refused, they were fired on. In Jadotville, 15 strikers were shot dead by the military.<ref name=\"Zeilig68\"/> In \u00c9lisabethville, the strikers, including their leader L\u00e9onard Mpoyi, were invited to negotiations at the town's stadium, where they were offered various concessions, including a 30% pay rise.<ref name=Zeilig68/> When the workers refused, the Governor of Katanga, Amour Maron, shot Mpoyi, killing him. The Governor then ordered his soldiers to fire on the other strikers in the stadium.<ref name=Zeilig69>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=69}}</ref> Between 60 and 70 strikers were killed during the protest,<ref name=BBC1/><ref>{{cite news|last=Mobe|first=Anicet|title=L'arm\u00e9e au Congo&nbsp;... |url=http://www.lalibre.be/debats/opinions/l-armee-au-congo-51b8d872e4b0de6db9c2b32a|accessdate=8 August 2013|newspaper=[[La Libre Belgique]]|date=18 August 2011}}</ref> although the official estimate was around 30.<ref>Transcription of the proceedings of the Council of Ministers of the government in exile, 18 December 1941, reproduced in {{cite web|title=Gr\u00e8ve \u00e0 L'Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga|url=http://www.expocongo.be/content.php?m=6&r=4&doc=218&l=fr|publisher=Expo Congo|accessdate=8 August 2013}}</ref> The miners returned to work on 10 December.<ref name=Zeilig69/>\n\nNumerous smaller strikes occurred in the Congo later in the war, though not on the same scale as in 1941. In 1944 strikes broke out in Katanga and [[Kasai region|Kasa\u00ef]], provoked by the conscription of workers for the mines and deteriorating working conditions.<ref name=IS1/> That year the Belgians conducted a few \"police operations\" in the province of [[\u00c9quateur (former province)|\u00c9quateur]] to ensure disgruntled labourers would collect rubber.{{sfn|Byfield et al.|2015|p=176}} In 1945, riots and strikes occurred among the black dockworkers in the port city of [[Matadi]].<ref name=IS1>{{cite journal|title=Congo (Editorial)|journal=[[International Socialism (magazine)|International Socialism]]|date=Autumn 1960|volume=1|issue=2|url=https://www.marxists.org/history/etol/newspape/isj/1960/isj002/editorial4.htm}}</ref><ref name=Murindwa14/>\n\n===Luluabourg mutiny===\nThe colonial government in the Congo depended on its military to maintain civil order and, above all, it depended on the loyalty of the native troops who made up the bulk of the Force Publique. Black [[non-commissioned officers]] led by [[Belgian military ranks|First Sergeant-Major]] Ngoie Mukalabushi, a veteran of the East African Campaign,<ref name=Mwamba1/> mutinied at [[Kananga|Luluabourg]] in the central Congolese province of Kasa\u00ef in February 1944;<ref name=Mwamba1>{{cite book|last=Mwamba Mputu|first=Baudouin|title=Le Congo-Kasa\u00ef (1865\u20131950): De l'exploration allemande \u00e0 la cons\u00e9cration de Luluabourg|year=2011|publisher=L'Harmattan|location=Paris|chapter=IV: Mutinerie de Luluabourg de 1944}}<!--Note that there are no page numbers in the book so cannot be cited--></ref> the trigger for this was a plan to vaccinate troops who had served at the front, though the soldiers were also unhappy about the demands placed on them and their treatment by their white officers.<ref name=Mwamba1/>\n\nThe mutineers broke into the base's armoury on the morning of 20 February and pillaged the white quarter of the town.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The town's inhabitants fled, and a Belgian officer and two white civilians were killed.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The mutineers attacked visible signs of the colonial authorities and proclaimed their desire for independence.<ref name=Mwamba1/> The mutineers then dispersed to their home villages, pillaging on the way;<ref name=Mwamba1/> they failed to spread the insurrection to neighbouring garrisons.<ref name=Zeilig69/> Two mutineers, including Mukalabushi, were executed for their part in the insurrection.<ref name=Mwamba1/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| footer = Medals awarded for service in the Force Publique ''([[1940\u20131945 African War Medal|left]])'' and in the colonial war effort ''([[1940\u20131945 Colonial War Effort Medal|right]])''.\n| image1 = M\u00e9daille de la Guerre Africaine 1940-1945 Belgique.jpg\n| width1 = 76\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = M\u00e9daille de l'Effort de Guerre Colonial 1940-1945 Belgique.jpg\n| width2 = 74<!--please do not modify. with this width, the photo is same length as other at 76...-->\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 = \n}}\nOfficial postwar Belgian rhetoric portrayed the Congo's attitude towards the mother country as one of \"unfailing solidarity.\"{{sfn|Veranneman|2014|p=133}} As a result of the Congo's comparative prosperity during the conflict, the post-war period saw a wave of immigration to the country from Belgium. By 1950, 100,000 whites were living in the Congo.<ref name=Larousse1/> Nevertheless, the war highlighted the precarious nature of the colonial administration, leading Governor Ryckmans to remark that \"the days of colonialism are over\" in 1946.<ref name=Zeilig70/> A feeling by the Belgian government prevailed that it had incurred a \"war debt\" to the Congo, and thus more attention was given to the concerns of the indigenous population.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=77}} In the years after the war, the colonial government underwent extensive reform.<ref name=Zeilig70/> Black people were granted significantly more rights and freedoms, leading to the growth of a so-called ''[[\u00c9volu\u00e9]]'' (\"evolved\") class.<ref name=Zeilig71>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=71}}</ref> Despite this, the Belgian policy of conscripted labour of 60 days a year from each native Congolese remained in effect until Congolese independence, whereas similar labour levies were abolished in British and French possessions after the war.{{sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soriano|2018|p=293}} Several black members of the Force Publique who were veterans of the war served in prominent roles in the army after Congolese independence, including [[Louis Bobozo]], [[Eugene Ebeya]] and [[Norbert Muke]].<ref name= mobe>{{cite news| last = Mob\u00e9 Fansiama | first = Anicet| title = H\u00e9ros m\u00e9connus de la seconde guerre mondiale| newspaper = Le Monde diplomatique| pages = 34\u201335| language = French| date = June 2007| url = https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/2007/06/MOBE_FANSIAMA/14833| access-date = 13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the industrial unrest, trade unions for black workers were instituted in 1946, though they lacked power and influence.<ref name=Zeilig70>{{cite book|last=Zeilig, Leo|first=Renton, David; Seddon, David|title=The Congo: Plunder and Resistance|year=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=1-84277-485-9|page=70}}</ref> Workers at the UMHK continued to demand higher wages, and strikes were common in the colony for the next decade.<ref name=Zeilig69/> Nevertheless, both wages and living conditions improved significantly in the years after the war.<ref name=Zeilig70/> The war began a second wave of industrialisation that lasted right up to Congolese independence in 1960.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buelens|first=Frans|author2=Cassimon, Danny|title=The Industrialization of the Belgian Congo|journal=\"Colonial Exploitation and Economic Development: The Belgian Congo and the Dutch East Indies Compared\" Conference|date=October 2011|url=http://vkc.library.uu.nl/vkc/seh/research/Lists/Events/Attachments/12/CH9.Buelens.Cassimon.IndustrializationCongo.pdf|location=University of Antwerp|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe 1941 \u00c9lisabethville massacre is a recurrent theme in Congolese art and folklore, and was later incorporated into the popular Congolese anti-colonial narrative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fabian|first=Johannes|authorlink=Johannes Fabian|title=Remembering the Present: Painting and Popular History in Zaire|year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=0-520-20376-3|pages=59\u201360|edition=2nd}}</ref> Historiographic discussion of the Congo's role in World War II is generally limited to mentions of the uranium extracted from Shinkolobwe.<ref>{{cite news| last = McCrummen| first = Stephanie| title = In Congo, men forced to fight in World War II are neglected, forgotten| newspaper = Boston Globe| page = A8| date = 9 August 2009}}</ref> The importance of Congolese uranium during the war caused the [[Soviet Union]] to become interested in the territory; it was subsequently an area of Soviet interest during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Borstelmann|first=Thomas|title=Apartheid, Colonialism, and the Cold War: the United States and Southern Africa, 1945\u20131952|year=1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=0-19-507942-6|pages=92\u201393}}</ref> The war also led to a re-orientation of the Congo's trade away from Belgium and towards the United States, the United Kingdom, and the United Kingdom's colonies.{{sfn|Martin|1985|pp=423\u2013424}}\n\n=== Commemoration ===\nIn 1943, a three-sided pyramid was erected in [[Faradje]], Belgian Congo to commemorate the actions of the Congolese in Ethiopia. Each face of the pyramid was inscribed with the name of each major location of fighting: Asosa, Gambela, and Sa\u00efo. Many locations throughout the country\u2014presently the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\u2014are named for the battles.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boneza |first=Ra\u00efs Neza |url=http://www.kimpavitapress.no/connecting-the-dot-congo-and-world-war-ii-one-of-the-other-forgotten-commemorations-by-ras-neza-boneza/ |access-date=10 March 2017 |title=Connecting the dot: Congo and World War II: One of the Other Forgotten Commemorations |publisher=Kimpavita Press & Publishers |location=Trondheim |date=7 June 2014}}</ref> In 1970 the Belgian government dedicated a monument in [[Schaerbeek]], Belgium, to the military successes of Belgian colonial forces, including those during World War II.{{sfn|Stanard|2009|p=112}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Democratic Republic of the Congo|World War II}}\n*[[Belgium in World War II]]\n*[[Free Belgian Forces]]\n*[[Ruzagayura famine]] (1943\u201344)\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Works cited ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Byfield|first1=Judith A.|last2=Brown|first2=Carolyn A.|last3=Parsons|first3=Timothy|last4=Sikainga|first4=Ahmad Alawad|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=tjoPCAAAQBAJ&dq=|title=Africa and World War II|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107053205|ref = {{harvid|Byfield et al.|2015}}}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Martin| first = Phyllis M.| title = Reviewed Work: Le Congo Belge durant la Seconde Guerre Mondiale: Recueil d'Etudes.| journal = The Journal of African History| volume = 26| issue = 4| pages = 422\u2013424| date = 1985| jstor = 181666| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Farrell-Robert| first = Janine| title = Glitter & Greed: The Secret World of the Diamond Cartel| publisher = Red Wheel Weiser| edition = revised| date = 2007| location =| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bHxgFQssc2IC| isbn = 9781609258801| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Fern\u00e1ndez Soriano| first = Victor| title = \u2018Travail et progr\u00e8s\u2019: Obligatory \u2018Educational\u2019 Labour in the Belgian Congo, 1933\u201360| journal = Journal of Contemporary History| volume = 53| issue = 2| pages = 292\u2013314| date = 2018| doi = 10.1177/0022009417697807| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Geenen| first = Kristien| title = Categorizing colonial patients: Segregated medical care, space and decolonization in a Congolese city, 1931\u201362| journal = The Journal of the International African Institute| volume = 89| issue = 1| pages = 100\u2013124| date = 2019| issn = 1750-0184| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch. Didier| title = The History of Congo | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| series = Greenwood histories of the modern nations| ISSN = 1096-2905| edition = illustrated, annotated| date = 2002| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780313316968| url-access = registration | isbn = 978-0-313-31696-8